# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: communist-party-of-britain
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on Thursday 11 June 1987, to elect 650 members to the House of Commons.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives ran a campaign focusing on lower taxes, a strong economy and strong defence.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] They also emphasised that unemployment had just fallen below the 3 million mark for the first time since 1981, and inflation was standing at 4%, its lowest level since the 1960s.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] National newspapers also continued to largely back the Conservative government, particularly *The Sun*, which ran anti–Labour Party articles with headlines such as "Why I'm backing Kinnock, by Stalin".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour, led by Neil Kinnock following Michael Foot's resignation in the aftermath of the party's landslide defeat at the 1983 general election, was slowly moving towards a more centrist policy platform, following the promulgation of a left-wing one under Foot's leadership.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The main aim of the Labour Party was to re-establish itself as the main progressive centre-left alternative to the Conservatives, after the rise of the Social Democratic Party (SDP) forced Labour onto the defensive; and Labour succeeded in doing so at this general election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The Alliance between the SDP and the Liberal Party was renewed, but co-leaders David Owen and David Steel could not agree whether to support either major party in the event of a hung parliament.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives were returned to government, having suffered a net loss of only 21 seats, which left them with 376 MPs and a reduced but still strong majority of 102 seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour succeeded in resisting the challenge by the SDP–Liberal Alliance to maintain its position as HM Official Opposition.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Moreover, Labour managed to increase its vote share in Scotland, Wales and the North of England.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Yet Labour still returned only 229 MPs to Westminster; and in certain London constituencies which Labour had held before the election, the Conservatives actually made gains.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was a disappointment for the Alliance, which saw its vote share fall and suffered a net loss of one seat as well as former SDP leader Roy Jenkins losing his seat to Labour.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] This led to the two Alliance parties merging completely soon afterwards to become the Liberal Democrats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] In Northern Ireland, the main unionist parties maintained their alliance in opposition to the Anglo-Irish Agreement; however, the Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) lost two seats to the Social Democratic and Labour Party (SDLP).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] One of the UUP losses was former Cabinet Minister Enoch Powell, famous for his stance against immigration, and formerly a Conservative MP.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] To date the Conservatives have not matched or surpassed their 1987 seat total in any general election held subsequently, although they recorded a greater share of the popular vote in the 2019 general election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The election night was covered live on the BBC, presented by David Dimbleby, Peter Snow and Robin Day.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] It was also broadcast on ITV, presented by Sir Alastair Burnet, Peter Sissons and Alastair Stewart.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The 1987 general election saw the election of the first Black Members of Parliament: Diane Abbott, Paul Boateng and Bernie Grant, all as representatives for the Labour Party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Other newcomers included future Cabinet members David Blunkett, John Redwood, John Reid, Andrew Smith and Alistair Darling, future Shadow Cabinet minister Ann Widdecombe, and future SNP Leader Alex Salmond.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservative campaign emphasised lower taxes, a strong economy and defence, and also employed rapid-response reactions to take advantage of Labour errors.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Norman Tebbit and Saatchi & Saatchi spearheaded the Conservative campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] However, when on "Wobbly Thursday" it was rumoured a Marplan opinion poll showed a narrow 2% Conservative lead, the "exiles" camp of David Young, Tim Bell and the advertising firm Young & Rubicam advocated a more aggressively anti-Labour message.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Bell and Saatchi & Saatchi produced memorable posters for the Conservatives, such as a picture of a British soldier's arms raised in surrender with the caption "Labour's Policy On Arms"—a reference to Labour's policy of unilateral nuclear disarmament.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The first Conservative party political broadcast played on the theme of "Freedom" and ended with a fluttering Union Jack, the hymn *I Vow to Thee, My Country* (which Thatcher would later quote in her "Sermon on the Mound") and the slogan "It's Great To Be Great Again".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour campaign was a marked change from previous efforts; professionally directed by Peter Mandelson and Bryan Gould, it concentrated on presenting and improving Neil Kinnock's image to the electorate.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour's first party political broadcast, dubbed *Kinnock: The Movie*, was directed by Hugh Hudson of *Chariots of Fire* fame, and concentrated on portraying Kinnock as a caring, compassionate family man.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] It was filmed at the Great Orme in Wales and had "Ode to Joy" and Brahms' 1st Symphony as its music.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] He was particularly critical of the high unemployment that the government's economic policies had resulted in, as well as condemning the wait for treatment that many patients had endured on the National Health Service.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Kinnock's personal popularity jumped 16 points overnight following the initial broadcast.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] On 24 May, Kinnock was interviewed by David Frost and claimed that Labour's alternative defence strategy in the event of a Soviet attack would be "using the resources you've got to make any occupation totally untenable".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] In a speech two days later Thatcher attacked Labour's defence policy as a programme for "defeat, surrender, occupation, and finally, prolonged guerrilla fighting ...
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] I do not understand how anyone who aspires to Government can treat the defence of our country so lightly".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher visited Buckingham Palace on 11 May and asked the Queen to dissolve Parliament on 18 May, announcing that the election would be held on 11 June.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives were returned by a second landslide victory after their first in 1983, with a comfortable majority, down slightly on 1983 with a swing of 1.5% towards Labour.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservative lead over Labour of 11.4% was the second-greatest for any party since the Second World War; surpassed only by the previous 1983 result.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Yet the overall result of this election proved that Margaret Thatcher's policies retained significant support.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Despite initial optimism and the professional campaign by Neil Kinnock, the election brought only twenty additional seats for Labour from the 1983 Conservative landslide.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] In many southern areas, the Labour vote actually fell, with the party losing seats in London.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] However, it represented a decisive victory against the SDP–Liberal Alliance and marked out the Labour Party as the main contender to the Conservative Party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] This was in stark contrast to 1983, when the Alliance votes almost matched Labour; although Labour had almost 10 times as many seats as the Alliance due to the structure of the First-Past-The-Post voting system.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The result for the Alliance was a disappointment, in that they had hoped to overtake Labour as the Official Opposition in the UK in terms of vote share.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Instead, they lost Roy Jenkins' seat and saw their vote share drop by almost 3%, with a widening gap of 8% between them and the Labour Party (compared to a 2% gap four years before).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] These results would eventually lead to the end of the Alliance and the birth of the Liberal Democrats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Most of the prominent MPs retained their seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Neil Kinnock increased his share of the vote in Islwyn by almost 12%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] Margaret Thatcher increased her share of the vote in her Finchley seat, but the Labour vote increased more, slightly reducing her majority.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] In Northern Ireland, the various unionist parties maintained an electoral pact (with few dissenters) in opposition to the Anglo-Irish Agreement.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] However, the Ulster Unionists lost two seats to the Social Democratic and Labour Party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives' victory could also arguably be attributed to the rise in living standards during their time in office.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] All parties gaining over 500 votes listed.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1987-united-kingdom-general-election] of disproportionality of the 1987 election was 17.82, between the Alliance and the Conservatives.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on Thursday, 1 May 1997.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The governing Conservative Party led by Prime Minister John Major was defeated in a landslide by the opposition Labour Party led by Tony Blair, which achieved a 177-seat majority and a total of 418 seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This was the first victory for the Labour party in a general election in nearly 23 years, its previous one registering a majority of 3 seats in October 1974 under the leadership of Harold Wilson.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] It was also Labour's first comprehensive victory over the Conservatives since the 1966 election, which had produced a 98-seat majority.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This election also marked Labour's highest vote share since the 1970 election and its second highest total number of votes in history (the largest being the 1951 election).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] On the other hand, it was an ignominious end to the 18-year government of the Conservatives, the longest continuous period of government of any party in modern British history.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This election marked the third-largest defeat ever suffered by the Conservatives (the largest being the 2024 election) with the party left with just 165 seats—it was left devoid of any MPs outside England, with only 17 MPs north of the Midlands, and with less than 20% of MPs in London.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Additionally, the party also registered its lowest share of the vote since 1832 as well as its lowest vote in absolute terms since 1929.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This would be the last election until 2024 that the Conservatives decreased their share of the vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The final result of the election on 2 May 1997 revealed that Labour had won a landslide majority, making a net gain of 146 seats and winning 43.2% of the vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] 150 Members of Parliament, including 133 Conservatives, lost their seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives, meanwhile, suffered defeat with a net loss of 178 seats, winning 30.7% of the vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Democrats led by Paddy Ashdown made a net gain of 28 seats, winning 16.8% of the vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour's victory, the largest achieved in its history and by any political party in British politics since the Second World War, brought about the party's first of three consecutive terms in power (lasting a total of 13 years), with Blair as the newly appointed prime minister.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Democrats' success in the election, in part due to anti-Conservative tactical voting, strengthened both Ashdown's leadership and the party's position as a strong third party, having won the highest number of seats by any third party since 1929.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The election of 120 women, including 101 to the Labour benches, came to be seen as a watershed moment in female political representation in the UK.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The British economy had been in recession at the time of the 1992 general election, which the governing Conservative Party led by John Major had won.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The recession ended within a year, but later events such as Black Wednesday severely tarnished the Conservative government's reputation for economic management.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Meanwhile, the opposition Labour Party elected John Smith as its leader in 1992 to succeed Neil Kinnock; however, Smith's death from a heart attack in 1994 led to a leadership election which was won by Shadow Home Secretary Tony Blair.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Blair sought to bring the party closer to the political centre of the era, including rebranding the party as "New Labour".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] He convinced the party's members and affiliated trades unions to support the removal of Clause IV from its constitution, which had committed it to the mass nationalisation of industry, and the party also reversed its policy on unilateral nuclear disarmament.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The events of Black Wednesday also meant Labour—and shadow chancellor Gordon Brown—were perceived as offering more competent economic management than the Conservatives.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Disputes within the Conservative government over European Union issues, and a variety of "sleaze" allegations, severely affected the government's popularity.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Despite the economic recovery and fall in unemployment in the four years leading up to the election, the rise in Conservative support was only marginal, with all of the major opinion polls showing Labour in a comfortable lead from late 1992 onwards.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the 1992 general election, the Conservatives remained in government with 336 of the 651 House of Commons seats, but through a series of defections and by-election defeats the government gradually lost its absolute majority.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] By 1997, the Conservatives held only 324 seats and had not won a by-election since Richmond in 1989.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The previous Parliament first sat on 27 April 1992.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Parliament Act 1911 required at the time for each Parliament to be dissolved on the fifth anniversary of its first sitting; therefore, the latest date the dissolution and the summoning of the next parliament could have been held on was 27 April 1997.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The 1985 amendment of the Representation of the People Act 1983 required that the election must take place on the eleventh working day after the deadline for nomination papers, which in turn must be no more than six working days after the next parliament was summoned.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Therefore, the latest date the election could have been held on was 22 May 1997 (which happened to be a Thursday).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] British elections (and referendums) have been held on Thursdays by convention since the 1930s, but can be held on other working days.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Major called the election on Monday 17 March 1997, ensuring the formal campaign would be unusually long, at six weeks (Parliament was dissolved on 8 April).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was scheduled for 1 May, to coincide with the local elections on the same day.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This set a precedent, as the three subsequent general elections were also held alongside the May local elections.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives argued that a long campaign would expose Labour and allow the Conservative message to be heard.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] However, Major was accused of arranging an early dissolution to protect Neil Hamilton from a pending parliamentary report into his conduct: a report that Major had earlier guaranteed would be published before the election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] In March 1997, soon after the election was called, Asda introduced a range of election-themed beers, these being "Major's Mild", "Tony's Tipple" and "Ashdown's Ale".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The political backdrop of campaigning focused on public opinion towards a change in government.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Opinion polls during campaigning showed strong support for Labour due to Blair's personal popularity, and Blair won a personal public endorsement from *The Sun* newspaper two months before the vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Major hoped that a long campaign would expose Labour's "hollowness" and the Conservative campaign emphasised stability, as did its manifesto title 'You can only be sure with the Conservatives'.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] However, the campaign was beset by deep-set problems, such as the rise of James Goldsmith's Referendum Party which advocated a referendum on continued membership of the European Union.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The party threatened to take away many right-leaning voters from the Conservatives.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Furthermore, about 200 candidates broke with official Conservative policy to oppose British membership of the single European currency.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Major fought back, saying: "Whether you agree with me or disagree with me; like me or loathe me, don't bind my hands when I am negotiating on behalf of the British nation." The moment is remembered as one of the defining, and most surreal, moments of the election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Meanwhile, there was also division amongst the Conservative cabinet, with Chancellor Kenneth Clarke describing the views of Home Secretary Michael Howard on Europe as "paranoid and xenophobic nonsense".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The New Labour, New Danger poster, which depicted Tony Blair with demon eyes, was an example of the latter strategy.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Major veered between the two approaches, which left Conservative Central Office staff frustrated.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] As Andrew Cooper explained: "We repeatedly tried and failed to get him to understand that you couldn't say that they were dangerous and copying you at the same time." In any case, the campaign failed to gain much traction, and the Conservatives went down to a landslide defeat at the polls.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour ran a slick campaign that emphasised the splits within the Conservative government and argued that the country needed a more centrist administration.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] It thus successfully picked up dissatisfied Conservative voters, particularly moderate and suburban ones.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Tony Blair, who was personally highly popular, was very much the centrepiece of the campaign and proved a highly effective campaigner.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour campaign was reminiscent of those of Bill Clinton for the US presidency in 1992 and 1996, focusing on centrist themes as well as adopting policies more commonly associated with the right, such as cracking down on crime and fiscal responsibility.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The influence of political "spin" came into great effect for Labour at this point, as media centric figures such as Alastair Campbell and Peter Mandelson provided a clear cut campaign, and establishing a relatively new political brand New Labour with enviable success.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] In this election Labour adopted the theme Things Can Only Get Better in their campaign and advertising.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Lib Dems promised to increase education funding paid for by a 1p increase in income tax.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was fought under new boundaries, with a net increase of eight seats compared to the 1992 election (651 to 659).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Changes listed here are from the notional 1992 result, had it been fought on the boundaries established in 1997.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] These notional results were calculated by Colin Rallings and Michael Thrasher and were used by all media organisations at the time.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour won a landslide victory with its largest parliamentary majority (177) to date.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] On the BBC's election night programme Professor Anthony King described the result of the exit poll, which accurately predicted a Labour landslide, as being akin to "an asteroid hitting the planet and destroying practically all life on Earth".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] After years of trying, Labour had convinced the electorate that they would usher in a new age of prosperity—their policies, organisation and tone of optimism slotting perfectly into place.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour's victory was largely credited to the charisma of Tony Blair, as well as a Labour public relations machine managed by Alastair Campbell and Peter Mandelson.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Between the 1992 election and the 1997 election there had also been major steps to "modernise" the party, including scrapping Clause IV that had committed the party to extending public ownership of industry.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour had suddenly seized the middle ground of the political spectrum, attracting voters much further to the right than their traditional working class or left wing support.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was a crushing defeat for the Conservatives, with the party having its lowest percentage share of the popular vote since 1832 under the Duke of Wellington's leadership, being wiped out in Scotland and Wales.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] A number of prominent Conservative MPs lost their seats in the election, including Michael Portillo, Malcolm Rifkind, Edwina Currie, David Mellor, Neil Hamilton and Norman Lamont.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Such was the extent of Conservative losses at the election that Cecil Parkinson, speaking on the BBC's election night programme, joked upon the Conservatives winning their second seat that he was pleased that the subsequent election for the leadership would be contested.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Democrats stood on a more left-wing manifesto than Labour, and more than doubled their number of seats thanks to the use of tactical voting against the Conservatives.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Although their share of the vote fell slightly, their total of 46 MPs was the highest for any UK Liberal party since David Lloyd George led the party to 59 seats in 1929.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Referendum Party, which sought a referendum on the United Kingdom's relationship with the European Union, came fourth in terms of votes with 800,000 votes and won no seats in parliament.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The six parties with the next highest votes stood only in either Scotland, Northern Ireland or Wales; in order, they were the Scottish National Party, the Ulster Unionist Party, the Social Democratic and Labour Party, Plaid Cymru, Sinn Féin, and the Democratic Unionist Party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The result declared for the constituency of Winchester showed a margin of victory of just two votes for the Liberal Democrats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This election saw a doubling of the number of women in parliament, from 60 elected in 1992 to 120 elected in 1997.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] 101 of them (controversially described as Blair Babes) were on the Labour benches, a number driven by the Labour Party's 1993 policy (ruled illegally discriminatory in 1996) of all-women shortlists.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This election has therefore been widely seen as a watershed moment for representation of women in the UK.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This election marked the start of Labour government for the next 13 years, lasting until the formation of the Conservative-Liberal Democrat coalition in 2010.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] All parties with more than 500 votes shown.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] and "Labour Time for Change" candidates; Conservative total includes candidates in Northern Ireland (excluded in some lists) and "Loyal Conservative" candidate.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The Popular Unionist MP elected in 1992 died in 1995, and the party folded shortly afterwards.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] There was no incumbent Speaker in the 1992 election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] The poor results for the Conservative Party led to infighting, with the One Nation group, Tory Reform Group, and right-wing Maastricht Rebels blaming each other for the defeat.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Party chairman Brian Mawhinney said on the night of the election that defeat was due to disillusionment with 18 years of Conservative rule.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] John Major resigned as party leader, saying "When the curtain falls, it is time to get off the stage".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Throughout this period, their representation in the Commons remained consistently below 200 MPs.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] Meanwhile, Paddy Ashdown's continued leadership of the Liberal Democrats was assured, and they were felt to be in a position to build positively as a strong third party into the new millennium, culminating in their sharing power in the 2010 coalition with the Conservatives.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] With the huge rise in internet use since the previous general election, BBC News created a special website – BBC Politics 97 – covering the election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/1997-united-kingdom-general-election] This site was an experiment for the efficiency of an online news service which was due for launch later in the year.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on 7 June 2001, four years after the previous election on 1 May 1997, to elect 659 members to the House of Commons.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The number of votes Labour received fell by nearly three million.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Blair went on to become the only Labour prime minister to serve two consecutive full terms in office.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] As Labour retained almost all of their seats won in the 1997 landslide victory, the media dubbed the 2001 election "the quiet landslide".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] There was little change outside Northern Ireland, with 620 out of the 641 seats in Great Britain electing candidates from the same party as they did in 1997.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] A strong economy contributed to the Labour victory.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The opposition Conservative Party under William Hague's leadership was still deeply divided on the issue of Europe and the party's policy platform had drifted considerably to the right.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The party put the issue of European monetary union, in particular the prospect of the UK joining the Eurozone, at the centre of its campaign but failed to resonate with the electorate.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives briefly had a narrow lead in the polls during the 2000 fuel strikes but Labour successfully resolved them by year end.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was largely a repeat of the 1997 general election, with Labour losing only six seats overall and the Conservatives making a net gain of one seat (gaining nine seats but losing eight).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives gained a seat in Scotland, which ended the party's status as an "England-only" party in the prior parliament, but failed again to win any seats in Wales.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Although they did not gain many seats, three of the few new MPs elected were future Conservative Prime Ministers David Cameron and Boris Johnson and future Conservative Chancellor of the Exchequer George Osborne; Osborne would serve in the same Cabinet as Cameron from 2010 to 2016.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Democrats led by Charles Kennedy made a net gain of six seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Exceptionally low voter turnout, which fell below 60% for the first time since 1918, also marked this election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was broadcast live on BBC One and presented by David Dimbleby, Jeremy Paxman, Andrew Marr, Peter Snow, and Tony King.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The 2001 general election was notable for being the first in which pictures of the party logos appeared on the ballot paper.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Prior to this, the ballot paper had only displayed the candidate's name, address, and party name.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The elections were marked by voter apathy, with turnout falling to 59.4%, the lowest (and first under 70%) since the Coupon Election of 1918.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Throughout the election the Labour Party had maintained a significant lead in the opinion polls and the result was deemed to be so certain that some bookmakers paid out for a Labour majority before election day.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] However, the opinion polls the previous autumn had shown the first Tory lead (though only by a narrow margin) in the opinion polls for eight years as they benefited from the public anger towards the government over the fuel protests which had led to a severe shortage of motor fuel.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] By the end of 2000, however, the dispute had been resolved and Labour were firmly back in the lead of the opinion polls.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] In total, a mere 29 parliamentary seats changed hands at the 2001 Election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] 2001 also saw the rare election of an independent.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Richard Taylor of Independent Kidderminster Hospital and Health Concern (usually now known simply as "Health Concern") unseated a government MP, David Lock, in Wyre Forest.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] There was also a high vote for British National Party leader Nick Griffin in Oldham West and Royton, in the wake of recent race riots in the town of Oldham.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] In Northern Ireland, the election was far more dramatic and marked a move by unionists away from support for the Good Friday Agreement, with the moderate Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) losing four seats to the more hardline Democratic Unionist Party (DUP).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] This polarisation was also seen in the nationalist community, with the moderate Social Democratic and Labour Party (SDLP) losing votes to the more staunchly left-wing, republican and abstentionist Sinn Féin.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] It also saw a tightening of the parties as the small UK Unionist Party lost its only seat.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The election had been expected on 3 May, to coincide with local elections, but on 2 April 2001, the local elections were postponed to 7 June because of rural movement restrictions imposed in response to the foot-and-mouth outbreak that had started in February.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] On 8 May, Prime Minister Tony Blair announced that the general election would be held on the 7 June as expected, on the same day as the local elections.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Blair made the announcement in a speech at St Saviour's and St Olave's Church of England School in Bermondsey, London rather than on the steps of Downing Street.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] For Labour, the last four years had run relatively smoothly.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The party had successfully defended all their by election seats, and many suspected a Labour win was inevitable from the start.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Many in the party, however, were afraid of voter apathy, which was epitomised in a poster of "Hague with Margaret Thatcher's hair", captioned "Get out and vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] For William Hague, however, the Conservative Party had still not fully recovered from the loss in 1997.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The party was still divided over Europe, and talk of a referendum on joining the Eurozone was rife; as a result, 'Save The Pound' was one of the key slogans deployed in the Conservatives' campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] As Labour remained at the political centre, the Conservatives moved to the right.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] A policy gaffe by Oliver Letwin over public spending cuts left the party with an own goal that Labour soon exploited.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Thatcher gave a speech to the Conservative Election Rally in Plymouth on 22 May 2001, calling New Labour 'rootless, empty and artificial'.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] She also added to Hague's troubles when speaking out strongly against the Euro to applause.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Hague himself, although a witty performer at Prime Minister's Questions, was dogged in the press and reminded of a speech he gave at the 1977 Conservative Conference.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] *The Sun* newspaper only added to the Conservatives' woes by backing Labour for a second consecutive election, calling Hague a 'dead parrot' during the Conservative Party's conference in October 1998.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives campaigned on a strongly right-wing platform, emphasising the issues of Europe, immigration and tax, the fabled 'Tebbit Trinity'.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Charles Kennedy contested his first election as leader of the Liberal Democrats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] During the election Sharron Storer, a resident of Birmingham, criticised Prime Minister Tony Blair in front of television cameras about conditions in the National Health Service.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The widely televised incident happened on 16 May during a campaign visit by Blair to the Queen Elizabeth Hospital in Birmingham.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Sharron Storer's partner, Keith Sedgewick, a cancer patient with non-Hodgkin lymphoma and therefore highly susceptible to infection, was being treated at the time in the bone marrow unit, but no bed could be found for him and he was transferred to the casualty unit for his first 24 hours.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] On the evening of the same day Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott punched a protestor after being hit by an egg on his way to an election rally in Rhyl, North Wales.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The election result was effectively a repeat of 1997, as the Labour Party retained an overwhelming majority, with the BBC announcing the victory at 2:58 am, Friday 8 June.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Having presided over relatively serene political, economic and social conditions, the feeling of prosperity in the United Kingdom had been maintained into the new millennium, and Labour would have a free hand to assert its ideals in the subsequent parliament.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Despite the victory, voter apathy was a major issue: turnout fell below 60%, 12 percentage points down on 1997.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] All three of the main parties saw their total votes fall, with Labour's total vote dropping by 2.8 million on 1997, the Conservatives' by 1.3 million, and the Liberal Democrats' by 428,000.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] This dramatic fall was widely attributed to the general acceptance of the status quo and the likelihood of Labour's majority remaining unassailable.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] For the Conservatives, the huge loss they had sustained in 1997 was repeated.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Despite gaining nine seats, they lost seven to the Liberal Democrats, and even one to Labour (South Dorset).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] William Hague was quick to announce his resignation, doing so at 7:44 am outside the Conservative Party headquarters.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Staying at what they considered rock bottom, however, showed that the Conservatives had failed to improve their negative public image, had remained somewhat divided over Europe and had not regained the trust that they had lost in the 1990s.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Hague's focus on the 'Save The Pound' campaign narrative had failed to gain any traction; Labour's successful counter-tactic was to be repeatedly vague over the issue of future monetary union – and said that the UK would only consider joining the Eurozone 'when conditions were right'.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] But in Scotland, despite flipping one seat from the Scottish National Party, their vote collapse continued.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] They failed to retake former strongholds in Scotland as the Nationalists consolidated their grip on the Northeastern portion of the country.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Democrats could point to steady progress under their new leader, Charles Kennedy, gaining six seats and thus building the performance of a pleasing 1997 election, where the party had more than doubled its parliamentary representation from 20 to 46 seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] Whilst they had yet to become electable as a government, they underlined their growing reputation as a worthwhile alternative to Labour and the Conservatives, inciting meaningful policy debates in Parliament and representing more than a mere protest vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The SNP failed to gain any new seats and lost a seat to the Conservatives, though by just 79 votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] In Wales, Plaid Cymru both gained a seat from Labour and lost one to them.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] In Northern Ireland, the Ulster Unionists, despite gaining North Down, lost five other seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2001-united-kingdom-general-election] The results of the election give a Gallagher index of dis-proportionality of 17.74.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on 5 May 2005, to elect 646 members to the House of Commons.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The governing Labour Party led by Prime Minister Tony Blair won its third consecutive victory, with Blair becoming the second Labour leader after Harold Wilson to form three majority governments.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] However, its majority fell to 66 seats; the majority it won four years earlier had been of 167 seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The UK media interpreted the results as an indicator of a breakdown in trust in the government, and especially in Blair.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] This was the first time the Labour Party had won a third consecutive election, but would be the last election victory for Labour until 2024.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Democrats, led by Charles Kennedy, increased its seat count for a third consecutive election, netting the most seats in its history until 2024 and the most of any of the connected British Liberal parties since 1923.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour campaign emphasised a strong economy; however, Blair had suffered a decline in popularity, which was exacerbated by the controversial decision to send British troops to invade Iraq in 2003.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives campaigned on policies such as immigration limits, improving poorly managed hospitals and reducing high crime rates.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Blair won a third term as prime minister, with Labour having 355 MPs, but with a popular vote share of just 35.2%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] This was the smallest of any majority government in UK electoral history until Keir Starmer won an even lower share in 2024.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] In terms of votes, Labour was only narrowly ahead of the Conservatives, but the party still held a comfortable lead in terms of seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives returned 198 MPs, with 32 more seats than they had won at the previous general election, and won the popular vote in England, though they still ended up with 91 fewer MPs in England than Labour.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Democrats saw their share of the popular vote increase by 3.7%, and won the most seats of any third party since 1923, with 62 MPs.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] In Northern Ireland, the Ulster Unionist Party (UUP), the more moderate of the main unionist parties, which had dominated Northern Irish politics since the 1920s, was reduced from six MPs to one, with party leader David Trimble himself being unseated.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The more hardline Democratic Unionist Party became the largest Northern Irish party, with nine MPs elected.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Stephen Twigg lost the Enfield Southgate constituency back to the Conservatives.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Notable MPs who joined the House of Commons at this election include future Labour leader and energy secretary Ed Miliband, future chancellor of the Exchequer and health secretary Jeremy Hunt, and future education secretary Michael Gove.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the election, Michael Howard conceded defeat, resigned as Conservative leader and was succeeded by future prime minister David Cameron.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Blair resigned as both prime minister and leader of the Labour Party in June 2007, and was replaced by Gordon Brown, the then–Chancellor of the Exchequer.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The election results were broadcast live on the BBC and presented by Peter Snow, David Dimbleby, Tony King, Jeremy Paxman and Andrew Marr.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The governing Labour Party, led by Tony Blair, was looking to secure a third consecutive term in office and to retain a large majority.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservative Party was seeking to regain seats lost to both Labour and the Liberal Democrats since the 1992 general election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Democrats hoped to make gains from both main parties, but especially the Conservative Party, with a 'decapitation' strategy which targeted members of the Shadow Cabinet.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The Lib Dems had the lofty ambition of forming either the Government or the Opposition, but more realistically hoped to play a major part in a parliament led by a minority Labour or Conservative government.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] In Northern Ireland the Democratic Unionist Party sought to make further gains from the Ulster Unionist Party in unionist politics, and Sinn Féin hoped to overtake the Social Democratic and Labour Party in nationalist politics.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] (Sinn Féin MPs do not take their seats in the House of Commons – they follow a policy of abstentionism.) Plaid Cymru and the pro-independence Scottish National Party stood candidates in every constituency in Wales and Scotland respectively.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Many seats were contested by other parties, including several parties without incumbents in the House of Commons.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Parties that were not represented at Westminster, but had seats in the devolved assemblies and/or the European Parliament, included the Alliance Party of Northern Ireland, the UK Independence Party, the Green Party of England and Wales, the Scottish Green Party, and the Scottish Socialist Party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The Health Concern party also stood again.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] A full list of parties which declared their intention to run can be found on the list of parties contesting the 2005 general election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] All parties campaigned using such tools as party manifestos, party political broadcasts and touring the country in what are commonly referred to as battle buses.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Local elections in parts of England and in Northern Ireland were held on the same day.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The polls were open for fifteen hours, from 7 am to 10 pm BST (UTC+1).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The election came just over three weeks after the dissolution of parliament on 11 April by Queen Elizabeth II, at the request of Prime Minister Tony Blair.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the death of Pope John Paul II on 2 April, it was announced that the calling of the election would be delayed until 5 April.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Thanks to eight years of sustained economic growth, Labour could point to a strong economy, with greater investment in public services such as education and health.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] This was overshadowed, however, by the issue of the controversial 2003 invasion of Iraq, which met widespread public criticism at the time and would dog Blair throughout the campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Chancellor Gordon Brown played a prominent role in the election campaign, frequently appearing with Blair and ensuring that the economy would remain the central focus of Labour's message.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Recently elected Conservative leader Michael Howard brought a great level of experience and stability to a party that had ousted its former leader Iain Duncan Smith just 18 months prior.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservative campaign was managed by Australian strategist Lynton Crosby.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour's counter-attack emphasised Howard's role in the unpopular Major Government of 1992–1997.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour aired a party election broadcast attacking Howard: a montage of scenes from Howard's tenure as Home Secretary, including prison riots and home repossessions.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] For the Liberal Democrats, this was the second and final election campaign fought by leader Charles Kennedy, who offered a more down-to-earth approach to voters and strongly opposed the Iraq War, both of which proved popular.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] There were some questions, however, over Kennedy's abilities: at the Liberal Democrat manifesto launch, he was asked about local income tax, but appeared confused on the figures.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Both the Liberal Democrats and the Conservatives were keen to tackle Labour's introduction of tuition fees, which both opposition parties opposed and promised to abolish.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] At the close of voting (2200 BST) the ballot boxes were sealed and returned to the counting centres, where counting proceeded under the supervision of the returning officer who was obliged to declare the result as soon as it was known.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] As previously, there was serious competition amongst constituencies to be first to declare.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The vote itself represented a swing (in a safe Labour seat, in a safe Labour region) of about 4% to the Conservatives and 4.5% to the Liberal Democrats, somewhat below the prediction of BBC/ITV exit polls published shortly after 2200 BST.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Sunderland North was the next to declare, followed by Houghton and Washington East, both of whose Labour MPs retained their seats but with reductions in the incumbent majorities of up to 9%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The first Scottish seat to declare was Rutherglen and Hamilton West — another safe Labour seat, also a Labour hold, but with the majority reduced by 4%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The first seat to change hands was Putney, where Labour's majority of 2,771 fell to a strong Conservative challenge, with a total swing of about 5,000 (6.2%).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] This was also the first seat to be declared for the Conservatives.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The first Liberal Democrat seat to be declared was North East Fife, the constituency of Lib Dem deputy leader Sir Menzies Campbell which he had held since 1987.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The constituency of Crawley in West Sussex had the slimmest majority of any seat, with Labour's Laura Moffatt holding off the Conservatives' Henry Smith by 37 votes after three recounts.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Following problems with exit polls in previous British elections, the BBC and ITV agreed for the first time to pool their respective data, using results from Mori and NOP.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] More than 20,000 people were interviewed for the poll at 120 polling stations across the country.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The predictions were exceptionally accurate – initial projections saw Labour returned to power with a majority of 66 (down from 160), and the final result was indeed a Labour majority of 66.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The projected shares of the vote in Great Britain were Labour 35%, Conservatives 33%, Liberal Democrats 22% and other parties 8%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] However, the Conservatives were expected to make the biggest gains – 44 seats according to the exit poll – with the Liberal Democrats expected to take as few as two.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Whilst the Lib Dems' vote share predicted by the exit poll was accurate (22.6% compared to the actual 22.0%), they did better in some Lib Dem – Labour marginal contests than predicted on the basis of the national share of the vote, and achieved a net gain of 11 seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] There were major boundary changes in Scotland, where the number of seats was reduced from 72 to 59.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] As a result of this each party lost some seats, and this notional election result below is based on the 2001 election results if they had been fought on these new 2005 boundaries.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] At 04:28 BST, it was announced that Labour had won Corby, giving them 324 seats in the House of Commons out of those then declared and an overall majority, Labour's total reaching 355 seats out of the 646 House of Commons seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour received 35.3% of the popular vote, equating to approximately 22% of the electorate on a 61.3% turnout, up from 59.4% turnout in 2001.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] As expected, voter disenchantment led to an increase of support for many opposition parties, and caused many eligible to vote, not to turn out.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour achieved a third successive term in office for the first time in their history, though with reduction of the Labour majority from 167 to 67 (as it was before the declaration of South Staffordshire).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] As it became clear that Labour had won an overall majority, Michael Howard, the leader of the Conservative Party, announced his intention to retire from frontline politics.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The final seat to declare was the delayed poll in South Staffordshire, at just after 1 am, Friday 24 June.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was followed by further criticism of the UK electoral system.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Calls for reform came particularly from Lib Dem supporters, citing that they received only just over 10% of the overall seats with 22.1% of the popular vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The only parties to win a substantially higher percentage of seats than they achieved in votes were Labour, the Democratic Unionist Party, Sinn Féin, [Health Concern]] (which ran only one candidate).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The results of the election give a Gallagher index of disproportionality of 16.76.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour's vote declined to 35.3%, a decline of 5.4% and the second lowest share of the popular vote to have formed a majority government in the House of Commons.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] In many areas the collapse in the Labour vote resulted in a host of seats changing hands.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour also failed to gain any new seats, almost unique in any election since 1945.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] As well as losing seats to the Tories and the Liberal Democrats, Labour also lost Blaenau Gwent, its safest seat in Wales, to Independent Peter Law, and Bethnal Green and Bow to Respect candidate George Galloway.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Nevertheless, the Labour government claimed that being returned to office for a third term for the first time ever showed the public approval of Labour's governance and the continued unpopularity of the Conservatives.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives asserted that their increased number of seats showed disenchantment with the Labour government.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The election result was later considered a precursor to the Conservative breakthrough at the next election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Democrats claimed that their continued increase in seats and percentage vote share over the past several elections showed they were in a position to make further gains from both parties.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Democrats also managed to take three seats from the Conservatives, one notable victory being that of Tim Farron over Tim Collins in Westmorland and Lonsdale, through the use of a 'decapitation strategy' which targeted senior Tories.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The party increased their percentage of the vote by 3.7% nationwide.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Meanwhile, the Scottish National Party improved its position in Scotland, regaining the Western Isles and Dundee East from Labour, having lost both seats in 1987.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] In Wales, Plaid Cymru failed to gain any seats and lost Ceredigion to the Liberal Democrats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] In Northern Ireland the Ulster Unionists were all but wiped out, only keeping North Down, with leader David Trimble losing his seat in Upper Bann.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] For the first time, the DUP became the biggest party in Northern Ireland.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] It was the first general election since 1929 in which no party received more than ten million votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] It was the most 'three-cornered' election since 1923, though the Liberal Democrats failed to match the higher national votes of the SDP–Liberal Alliance in the 1980s.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] In fact, the total combined vote for Labour, the Conservatives and the Liberal Democrats proved to be the lowest main three-party vote since 1922.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The figure of 355 seats for Labour does not include the Speaker Michael Martin.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] See also the list of parties standing in Northern Ireland.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the election, Labour remained in power with Tony Blair remaining as Prime Minister.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The morning after the election, Blair travelled to Buckingham Palace to inform The Queen of the election result and to receive permission to form a government, consequently beginning his third term as prime minister.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Blair reshuffled his Cabinet and junior ministers over the following weekend, with formal announcements made on 9 May 2005.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The most senior positions of Chancellor, Home Secretary and Foreign Secretary remained the same (Gordon Brown, Charles Clarke and Jack Straw respectively), but a few new faces were added.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Most notably, David Blunkett returned to cabinet as the Work and Pensions Secretary, although he was forced to resign again due to another scandal before the end of the year that spawned a national press and opposition campaign for his dismissal.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Patricia Hewitt became the new Health Secretary, Tessa Jowell remained as Culture Secretary, whilst Alan Johnson was promoted to Trade and Industry Secretary.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Meanwhile, Ruth Kelly retained the Education job and Margaret Beckett stayed put at Environment.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament met on 11 May for the election of the Speaker of the House of Commons.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] On 6 May, Michael Howard announced he would be standing down as leader of the Conservative Party, but not before a review of the leadership rules.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The formal leadership election began in October, and was ultimately won by David Cameron.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] On 7 May, David Trimble resigned as leader of the Ulster Unionist Party; Sir Reg Empey was elected as his successor at an Ulster Unionist Council meeting on 24 June.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] Blair's successor as Prime Minister, Gordon Brown (who came to office on 27 June 2007), visited Buckingham Palace on 6 April 2010 and asked the Queen to dissolve Parliament on 12 April.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2005-united-kingdom-general-election] The next election was held on 6 May 2010.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The **2009 European Parliament election** was the United Kingdom's component of the 2009 European Parliament election, the voting for which was held on Thursday 4 June 2009.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The election was held concurrently with the 2009 local elections in England.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] 72 members of the European Parliament (MEPs) were elected from the United Kingdom using proportional representation.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The election was won by the Conservative Party, who won 27 seats with a share of 27.9% of the national vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] This was the last European election in the United Kingdom at which either the Conservatives or the Labour Party finished in first place.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Other notable outcomes were that Labour – which came third – suffered a significant drop in support, and that the UK Independence Party (UKIP) finished second in a major election for the first time in its history, coming level with Labour in terms of seats but ahead of it in terms of votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] This was the first time in British electoral history that a party in government had been outpolled in a national election by a party with no representation in the House of Commons.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The British National Party (BNP) also won two seats, its first ever in a nationwide election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] It also marked the first time the Scottish National Party (SNP) won the largest share of the European election vote in Scotland, and the first time Labour had failed to come first in a Welsh election since 1918.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] It was the Democratic Unionist Party (DUP)'s worst ever European election result, and also the first time an Irish Republican party, Sinn Féin, topped the polls in Northern Ireland.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The United Kingdom elected 72 members of the European Parliament using proportional representation.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] It was divided into twelve multi-member constituencies, or regions.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The eleven of these regions which form Great Britain used a closed-list party list system method of proportional representation, calculated using the D'Hondt method.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Northern Ireland used the single transferable vote (STV).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The experimental use of all-postal ballots in four regions in 2004 was not repeated, resulting in a sharp reduction in turnout in those regions.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] As had been the case since 1999, the electoral constituencies were based on the government's nine English regions, Scotland, Northern Ireland and Wales, creating a total of 12 constituencies.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Treaty of Nice fixed the number of MEPs for the whole European Parliament at 736; as a consequence of the accession of Romania and Bulgaria in 2007, the number of seats allocated to the United Kingdom was reduced from 78 to 72.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] If the Treaty of Lisbon had entered into force by June 2009, this figure would have been 73.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] On 31 July 2007, in line with the required reduction in representation from the United Kingdom, the number of members elected from each region was modified by the Boundary Commission and Electoral Commission, based on the size of the electorate in each region.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The recommended changes were approved by the Parliament of the United Kingdom in 2008.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] In the run up to the election, several polling organisations carried out public opinion polling in regards to voting intentions in Great Britain.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Results of such polls are displayed below.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] ComRes, ICM, Populus and YouGov are members of the British Polling Council, and abide by its disclosure rules.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] BPIX is not a member of the BPC, and does not publish detailed methodology and findings.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] ‡ As the number of seats was reduced, these are notional changes estimated by the BBC.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Joint ticket, ran in England as: The Christian Party - Christian Peoples Alliance.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Turnout in Great Britain was 34.3%, with 15,137,202 votes out of a total electorate of 44,171,778.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Most of the results of the election were announced on Sunday 7 June, after similar elections were held in the other 26 member states of the European Union.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Scotland declared its result on Monday 8 June, as counting in the Western Isles was delayed due to observance of the Sabbath.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Great Britain kept to the Europe-wide trend towards the right.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Labour Party, which was in its twelfth year of government of the United Kingdom, polled third and suffered a significant drop in support; UKIP finished second in a major election for the first time in its history, coming level with Labour in terms of seats but ahead of it in terms of votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Conservatives won in every region in Great Britain except the North East, where Labour won, and Scotland, where the SNP won.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Labour suffered most notably in Cornwall, where it came sixth behind Mebyon Kernow, and in the wider South West region and South East, where it polled fifth behind the Green Party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The British National Party won two seats, its first ever in a national election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The share of the vote achieved by the English Democrats doubled.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The turnout in Scotland was the lowest in the United Kingdom at 28.8%, with 1,104,512 votes out of a total electorate of 3,872,975.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] In Scotland it was the first time the SNP won the largest share of the European election vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The SNP share of the vote rose by 9.4% points compared to 2004; this was the biggest positive swing for any party in any region in Great Britain.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] In Wales it was the first time since 1918 that Labour had failed to come first in a Welsh election, dropping 12.2%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] In Wales the Conservative Party topped the poll, with the nationalist Plaid Cymru coming a close third.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] UKIP took the fourth Welsh seat, the first time Wales had elected a UKIP MEP.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Both the Liberal Democrats and the Green Party polled their lowest regional shares in Wales, though Wales was the only region where the Liberal Democrat share of the vote rose compared with 2004.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] †Seat change has been adjusted to allow for direct comparison with the results from the 2004 election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Gibraltar is a British overseas territory (BOT) and therefore is under the jurisdiction and sovereignty of the United Kingdom but does not form part of it.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Gibraltar was, however, part of the EU, the only BOT to be so, and participated as part of the South West England constituency.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Turnout was 35% in Gibraltar, below the 39% for the South West England electoral region as a whole and significantly lower than the turnout in Gibraltar in 2004.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The Conservatives won with 53.3% of the votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Labour narrowly retained second place achieving 19% to the Liberal Democrats' 18.2%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] It was the DUP's worst ever European election result: the party had previously topped the poll in every European election in Northern Ireland since the first one in 1979.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] It was also the first time an Irish Republican topped the poll, Bairbre de Brún of Sinn Féin coming first with 125,000 votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The share of the votes for most parties in Northern Ireland remained essentially unchanged, the main exceptions were the DUP where their share of the vote fell by 13.8%, and the TUV, a party created by former DUP MEP Jim Allister whose share of the vote rose 13.7%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The DUP's decreased vote share was largely blamed on the TUV splitting the vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Gordon Brown faced calls for him to resign as Prime Minister following Labour's defeat.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] During the 2005 Conservative leadership election, David Cameron argued for withdrawal of the Conservatives from EPP-ED and for the formation of a new group.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] After the European election it was announced that the Conservatives were leaving the EPP-ED and forming a new group, the European Conservatives and Reformists.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] On 22 June 2009, the first official list of the new group's members was released.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The group held its inaugural meeting on 24 June, during which Conservative MEP Timothy Kirkhope was named interim leader.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The first election for the group leadership was also scheduled for 14 July, pitting interim leader Kirkhope against fellow Briton Geoffrey Van Orden.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Kaminski's bid for Vice-President of the European Parliament subsequently failed, and the Poles threatened to abandon the new caucus unless Kaminski was made the group leader in the parliament.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Similarly, UKIP helped found a new European Parliament Group, Europe of Freedom and Democracy, after the other parties in UKIP's pre-election European parliamentary grouping, Independence/Democracy, had polled badly.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2009-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Of the two BNP candidates elected to the European Parliament at the 2009 election, the UK Government announced that it would provide them both with only the bare minimum level of support, denying them the ready access to officials and information that the other 70 British MEPs received.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on 6 May 2010 to elect 650 MPs to the House of Commons.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This was the first election to be held after the minimum age of candidacy was reduced from 21 to 18.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It remains the last election in the UK to produce a Prime Minister who lasted a full term.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It resulted in the Labour government losing its 66-seat majority; however, with the opposition Conservative Party ending up with only 306 elected MPs, it was also the first election since that of February 1974 to result in a hung parliament.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives entered government (at first in partnership with the Liberal Democrats) and remained in office for 14 years until 2024.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] During the campaign, the three main party leaders engaged in the first televised debates.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats achieved a breakthrough in opinion polls following the first debate, in which their leader Nick Clegg was widely seen as the strongest performer.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Nonetheless, on polling day their share of the vote increased by only 1%, with a net loss of five seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This was still the Liberal Democrats' largest popular vote since the party's creation in 1988; they found themselves in a pivotal role in the formation of the new government.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The share of votes for parties other than Labour or the Conservatives was 35%, the largest since the 1918 general election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It was the most 'three-cornered' election in terms of votes since 1923, and in terms of seats since 1929.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Green Party of England and Wales won its first ever seat in the House of Commons, and the Alliance Party of Northern Ireland also gained its first elected member.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The general election saw a 5.1% national swing from Labour to the Conservatives, the third-largest since 1945.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The result in one constituency, Oldham East and Saddleworth, was subsequently declared void on petition because of illegal practices during the campaign (see 2011 Oldham East and Saddleworth by-election); it was the first such instance since 1910.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A hung parliament had been largely anticipated by the opinion polls in the run-up to the election, so politicians and voters were better prepared for the constitutional process that would follow such a result than they had been in 1974.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The coalition government that was subsequently formed was the first to result directly from a UK election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The hung parliament came about in spite of the Conservatives managing a higher share of the vote than the previous Labour government had done in 2005, when it had secured a comfortable majority.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Coalition talks began immediately between the Conservatives and the Liberal Democrats, and lasted for five days.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] There was an attempt to put together a Labour – Liberal Democrat coalition (though 11 seats from other smaller parties would have been required).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] To facilitate this, Gordon Brown announced on the evening of Monday 10 May that he would resign as Leader of the Labour Party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Just after midnight on 12 May, the Liberal Democrats approved the coalition agreement 'overwhelmingly'.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A total of 149 sitting MPs stood down at the election, the highest since 1945, including many former New Labour Cabinet ministers such as former Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott, Alan Milburn, Geoff Hoon, Ruth Kelly, James Purnell and John Reid.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] One reason for the very high number of MPs standing down was the parliamentary expenses scandal a year earlier.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A record 228 new MPs were elected at the election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Many of the Conservative MPs elected for the first time became ministers in government.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The election took place on 6 May in 649 constituencies across the United Kingdom, under the first-past-the-post system, for seats in the House of Commons.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Voting in the Thirsk and Malton constituency was postponed for three weeks because of the death of a candidate.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The governing Labour Party campaigned to secure a fourth consecutive term in office, and to restore support lost since 2001 due to the Iraq War.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservative Party sought to gain a dominant position in British politics after losses in the 1990s, and to replace Labour as the governing party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats hoped to make gains from both sides and hoped to hold the balance of power in a hung parliament.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Since the televised debates between the three leaders, the Lib Dems' poll ratings had risen to the point where many considered the possibility of a role for the party in forming the government.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Polls just before election day saw a slight swing from the Liberal Democrats back to Labour and Conservatives, with the majority of final polls falling within one point of each of the three parties' final vote shares.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Scottish National Party, encouraged by its victory in the 2007 Scottish parliament elections, set itself a target of 20 MPs and was hoping to find itself holding a balance of power, though it ultimately fell short, winning just 6 seats – the same as in 2005.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Smaller parties which had achieved success at local elections and the 2009 European elections (UK Independence Party, Green Party, British National Party, etc.) looked to extend their representation to seats in the House of Commons.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Greens successfully achieved their first-ever seat in the House of Commons – Caroline Lucas won the constituency of Brighton Pavilion, marking a historic breakthrough for the party – though other parties failed to win any seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Democratic Unionist Party looked to maintain, if not extend, its number of seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, they instead fell from 9 to 8 seats, though they maintained their position as the fourth-largest party in the House of Commons.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This election had an unusually high number of MPs choosing not to seek re-election, with more standing down than did so at the 1945 general election (which on account of the extraordinary wartime circumstances came ten years after the preceding election).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This has been attributed to the 2009 expenses scandal and the fact there was talk that redundancy-style payments for departing MPs might be scrapped after the election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In all, 149 MPs (100 Labour, 35 Conservatives, 7 Liberal Democrats, 2 Independents, 1 Independent Conservative and 1 member each from the SNP, Plaid Cymru, the DUP, and the SDLP) decided not to contest the election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Additionally, three seats were vacant at the time of the dissolution of Parliament; two due to the deaths of Labour MPs and one due to the resignation in January 2010 of a DUP member.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Pursuant to Boundary Commission for England recommendations, the number of seats in England increased by four, and numerous changes were made to the existing constituency boundaries.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Northern Ireland continued to elect 18 MPs, but minor changes were made to the eastern constituencies in accordance with the Northern Ireland Boundary Commission's recommendations.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] For the first time, these changes include the splitting of an electoral ward between two constituencies.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] At the time of the election Welsh constituencies had electorates on average around 14,000 smaller than their counterparts in England.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Scotland saw its most recent large-scale review completed in 2004, so its 59 constituencies remained the same as at the 2005 general election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] For the leaders of all three major political parties, this was their first general election contest as party leader – something that had last occurred at the 1979 election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The prospect of a coalition or minority government was being considered well before polling day.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Gordon Brown made comments about the possibility of a coalition in January 2010.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In 2009, it was reported that senior civil servants were to meet with the Liberal Democrats to discuss their policies, an indication of how seriously the prospect of a hung parliament was being taken.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Since that election, the SNP had won the 2007 Scottish Parliament elections and gained control of the Scottish Government, and also won the largest share of the 2009 European Parliament election vote in Scotland.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In Wales, the Labour Party remained the largest party in the Welsh Assembly, although Plaid Cymru increased their share of the vote and formed a coalition government with Labour.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In 2009 the Ulster Unionist Party and the Conservative Party announced they had formed an electoral alliance whereby the two parties would field joint candidates for future elections under the banner of "Ulster Conservatives and Unionists – New Force".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, this caused the sole UUP MP Lady Sylvia Hermon to resign from the party on 25 March 2010, leaving them with no representation at Westminster for the first time in their history.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Many constituencies were contested by other, smaller parties.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In 2009, Nigel Farage announced his intention to resign as UKIP leader to focus on becoming an MP.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Farage was replaced in an election by party members by Lord Pearson of Rannoch, whose stated intention was for the electoral support of UKIP to force a hung parliament.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Green Party of England and Wales voted to have a position of leader for the first time; the first leadership election was won by Caroline Lucas, who successfully contested the constituency of Brighton Pavilion.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In addition, a new loose coalition, Trade Unionist and Socialist Coalition (TUSC), contested a general election for the first time.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Several members of these unions ran as candidates under the TUSC banner.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, some former members of NO2EU, such as the Liberal Party and the Communist Party of Britain, chose not to participate in the TUSC campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The coalition did not run candidates against left wing Labour or Respect candidates.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The UKIP candidate for Thirsk and Malton—John Boakes—died, causing the election in the constituency to be postponed until 27 May.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Philip Lardner, the Conservative candidate for North Ayrshire and Arran, was suspended from the party for comments he made about homosexuality on his website, describing it as not "normal behaviour".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A total of 2,378 postal voters in Bristol West were wrongly sent ballot papers for Bristol East by mistake.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The SNP attempted but failed to ban the broadcast of the final party leaders' debate in Scotland, in a court action.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] They had argued that "the corporation [the BBC] had breached its rules on impartiality by excluding the SNP".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The judge, Lady Smith, ruled that "the SNP's case 'lacks the requisite precision and clarity'" and added she could not "conclude the BBC had breached impartiality rules".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Additionally, broadcasting regulator Ofcom ruled that it had not "upheld complaints received from the SNP and Plaid Cymru about The First Election Debate broadcast on ITV1 on Thursday 15 April 2010".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The leader of the UK Independence Party, Lord Pearson, wrote an open letter to Somerset newspapers, asking voters to support Conservative candidates, rather than UKIP candidates in the Somerton and Frome, Taunton Deane and Wells constituencies.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This action was criticised by UKIP candidates who refused to stand down.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Labour candidate for Bristol East and former MP Kerry McCarthy revealed information about postal votes cast in the constituency on Twitter.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Avon and Somerset Police said they were "looking into a possible alleged breach of electoral law".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The former Prime Minister Tony Blair returned to the campaign trail for Labour, visiting a polyclinic in Harrow West, following a troubled Labour campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Postal voters in the marginal Vale of Glamorgan constituency had to be issued with new ballot papers after mistakenly being told they did not have to sign applications for postal votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A group of entrepreneurs warned on the dangers of a Labour-Liberal coalition in an open letter to *The Times* on 29 April.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 28 April, Gordon Brown met Gillian Duffy, a 65-year-old woman and lifelong Labour voter from Rochdale, a Labour–Liberal Democrat marginal seat.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Brown's remarks were inadvertently recorded by a Sky News microphone he was still wearing, and widely broadcast.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour sources later stated that Brown had misheard Duffy and thought she had asked, "where are they fucking from?" Soon after the incident, Brown talked to Jeremy Vine live on BBC Radio 2 and publicly apologised to Duffy.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] American comedian Jon Stewart commented that the clip showed the moment when Brown's "political career leaves his body".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Brown subsequently visited Duffy to apologise in person.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Upon emerging, he described himself as a "penitent sinner", while Duffy refused to speak to the press and would not shake hands with him in front of the cameras.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] She said the incident had left her feeling more sad than angry and that she would not be voting for Labour or any other party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The incident was subsequently dubbed "Bigotgate", which was later added to the Collins English Dictionary.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Despite this, Labour went on to gain the Rochdale seat from the Liberal Democrats, one of the few gains they made in the election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In Hornsey and Wood Green constituency 749 postal voters were sent ballot papers which asked voters to pick three candidates instead of one; Haringey Council had to send correct versions by hand.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Metropolitan Police launched an investigation in the London Borough of Tower Hamlets.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] *The Times* reported on 2 May that the investigation had revealed some names on the register were fictitious, with a late surge in applications to be added to the electoral register (before 20 April deadline) leading to 5,000 additions without time for full checks.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In terms of the outcome of the borough's two seats, the narrower majority in any event exceeded 5,000 votes in Poplar and Limehouse, at 6,030 votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Labour candidate for North West Norfolk, Manish Sood, described Gordon Brown as Britain's worst ever prime minister.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The comments, which he repeated to a variety of news outlets, took attention away from the previous day's speech by Brown to Citizens UK, widely described as his best in the campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A Conservative Party activist in Peterborough was arrested after alleged postal voting fraud, calling into question 150 postal votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Simon Bennett resigned as the head of the British National Party's online operation then redirected its website to his own on which he attacked the party's leadership.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On the morning of polling day, 6 May, the former and later leader of UKIP, Nigel Farage, standing in Buckingham against the Speaker, was injured when a light banner-towing aircraft in which he was a passenger crashed near Brackley, Northamptonshire.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Groups of voters waiting in queues at 10 pm were locked out of polling stations in Sheffield Hallam, Manchester and Leeds; and police said one London polling station was open until 10.30 pm, which triggered a national review of polling station requirements led by the Electoral Commission.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The counts for the Foyle and East Londonderry constituencies were suspended because of a security alert around 11 pm after a car was abandoned outside the counting centre, causing a bomb scare.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The SNP insisted that as the leading political party in Scotland in the latest opinion poll, it should be included in any debate broadcast in Scotland.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 22 December 2009, the UKIP leader, Lord Pearson stated that his party should also be included.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Following a decision by the BBC Trust not to uphold a complaint from the SNP and Plaid Cymru over their exclusion from the planned BBC debate, the SNP announced on 25 April that they would proceed with legal action over the debate scheduled for 29 April.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The party said it was not trying to stop the broadcast but it wanted an SNP politician included for balance.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The SNP lost the case, in a judgement delivered on 28 April.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Since each MP is elected separately by the first past the post voting system, it is impossible to precisely project a clear election outcome from overall UK shares of the vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Not only can individual constituencies vary markedly from overall voting trends, but individual countries and regions within the UK may have a very different electoral contest that is not properly reflected in overall share of the vote figures.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Immediately following the previous general election, Labour held a double-digit lead in opinion polls.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, over the course of 2005, this lead was eroded somewhat.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] By December 2005, the Conservative party showed its first small leads in opinion polls following the controversial 90 days' detention proposals and the election of David Cameron to the leadership of the Conservative party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In early 2006, opinion polls were increasingly mixed with small leads given alternately to Labour and Conservative.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] From the May 2006 local elections, in which Labour suffered significant losses, the Conservatives took a small single-digit lead in opinion polls.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour regained the lead in June 2007 following the resignation of Tony Blair and the appointment of Gordon Brown as prime minister.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] From November 2007, the Conservatives again took the lead and, from then, extended their lead into double digits, particularly in response to the MPs' expenses scandal, although there was some evidence that the lead narrowed slightly towards the end of 2009.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] By the end of February 2010, Ipsos MORI, ICM, YouGov and ComRes polls had all found a sufficient narrowing of the Conservative lead for media speculation about a hung parliament to return.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] From 15 April 2010, following the first televised debate of the party leaders, polling data changed dramatically, with the Lib Dem vote proportion rising to 28–33%, and the Conservative vote proportion falling.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] In some polls, the Liberal Democrats took the lead from the Conservatives.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Under UNS projections, this made a hung parliament highly probable, if Lib Dem performance had persisted.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] After the second debate on 22 April the polls, on average, placed the Conservatives in the lead on 33%, the Liberal Democrats in second on 30% and Labour in third on 28%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] If these polls had reflected the election day results on a uniform swing nationwide, Labour would have had the most seats in a hung Parliament.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] At 22:00 on election day, coinciding with the closure of the polls, the results of an exit poll completed by GfK NOP and Ipsos MORI on behalf of the BBC, Sky and ITV news services was announced.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Data were gathered from individuals at 130 polling stations around the country.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The results of the poll initially suggested a hung parliament with the Conservative Party 19 seats from a controlling majority; this was later adjusted to 21 seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The distribution of seats between the Conservatives, Labour, Liberal Democrats and other parties was initially suggested to be 307, 255, 59 and 29, respectively, although the seat numbers were later changed to 303, 251, 69 and 27, respectively.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Initial reaction to the exit poll by various commentators was of surprise at the apparent poor prospects for the Liberal Democrats because it was at odds with many opinion polls undertaken in the previous weeks.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The actual results showed that the exit poll was a good predictor.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A later BBC Exit poll (05:36 BST) predicted the Conservatives on 306 (20 short of an overall majority), Labour on 262 and Liberal Democrats on 55.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] National newspapers in England traditionally endorse political parties before a general election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The following table shows which parties the major papers endorsed.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Turnout nationally was 65%, a rise from the 61% turnout in the 2005 general election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 27 May 2010 the Conservatives won the final seat of Thirsk and Malton, thus giving them 306 seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The election in that constituency had been delayed because of the death of the UKIP candidate.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Two results were also challenged by defeated candidates through election petitions – Fermanagh and South Tyrone, and Oldham East and Saddleworth.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] These candidates had lost by 4 and 103 votes respectively.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The defeated Unionist 'Unity' candidate, Rodney Connor, lodged a petition against the successful Sinn Féin candidate, Michelle Gildernew, in Fermanagh and South Tyrone, alleging irregularities in the counting of the votes had affected the result.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Gildernew had won with a plurality of four votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] However, the court found that there were only three ballot papers which could not be accounted for, and even if they were all votes for Connor, Gildernew would have had a plurality of one.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On 28 May 2010, the defeated Liberal Democrat candidate Elwyn Watkins lodged a petition against the election of Phil Woolas (Labour) in Oldham East and Saddleworth constituency.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The petition challenged leaflets issued by Woolas's campaign as having contained false statements of fact concerning Watkins' personal character, which is an illegal practice under section 106 of the Representation of the People Act 1983.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The statements attempted to link Watkins with Muslim extremists and death threats to Woolas, accused him of reneging on a promise to live in the constituency, and implied that his campaign was funded by illegal foreign political donations.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] During the court case a number of emails between Woolas and his campaign team emerged.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] On that day Woolas was found to have breached section 106 of the Representation of the People Act 1983 in relation to three of the four statements complained about, and the judges ruled that his election was void.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Phil Woolas applied for a judicial review into the ruling, stating that "this election petition raised fundamental issues about the freedom to question and criticise politicians" and that it "will inevitably chill political speech".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] He succeeded in overturning the finding in respect of one of the three statements but the main findings of the election court judgment were upheld.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] A by-election on 13 January 2011 resulted in the election of Debbie Abrahams (Labour).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] At 9:41 on 7 May, the BBC confirmed a hung parliament.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives stood at 290 seats, Labour at 247 and Liberal Democrats at 51.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] One constituency seat (Thirsk and Malton) was contested on 27 May because of the death of the UKIP candidate and was won by the Conservative Party, whilst another seat (Oldham East and Saddleworth) later had its result declared void; Labour won the resulting by-election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The result showed an overall 5.1% swing from Labour to the Conservatives, the third largest national swing achieved in a general election since 1945 and similar to the 5.3% swing achieved by the Conservative leader Margaret Thatcher in 1979.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The 97 net seat gains made by the Conservatives outdid their previous best gains total in 1950, when they gained 85.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour's loss of 91 seats was worse than their previous greatest loss of seats, when they lost 77 seats in 1970.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Of the 532 seats contested in England (a final seat, Thirsk and Malton, was contested on 27 May), the Conservatives won 298 seats and an absolute majority of 61 seats over all other parties combined, securing an average swing of 5.6% from Labour.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour did poorly in many Southern areas, notably in the Eastern Region where they won only two of their 14 seats from 2005: Luton North and Luton South.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour did, however, gain two seats: Bethnal Green and Bow and Chesterfield.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The Conservatives made 95 of their gains in England, but they also suffered three losses, all to the Liberal Democrats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] For the Liberal Democrats, their eight gains were overshadowed by their 12 losses – one to Labour and 11 to the Conservatives.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The British National Party (BNP) would record their highest ever vote in a general election with 1.9% of the popular vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This is the highest vote for a British Far-right party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] None of Scotland's 59 seats changed hands and all were held by the same party that had won them at the 2005 election, with Labour regaining the two seats they had lost in by-elections since 2005.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] There was a swing to Labour from the Conservatives of 0.8% (with Labour increasing its share of the vote by 2.5% and the Conservatives increasing by just 0.9%) The Conservatives finished with just a single MP representing a Scottish constituency.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Of the 40 seats contested in Wales, the Conservatives more than doubled their seats from three to eight, taking one from the Liberal Democrats and four from Labour.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Welsh nationalist party Plaid Cymru's number of seats was reduced from three to two on the new seat boundaries, but they managed to gain one seat, Arfon, from Labour.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Labour did, however, regain Blaenau Gwent, which had once been Labour's safest seat in Wales until it had been taken by an Independent, Peter Law, in 2005.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Overall, Labour made a net loss of 4 seats but remained the biggest party, with 26.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] There were 18 seats contested in Northern Ireland.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] Both Irish nationalist parties, Sinn Féin and the Social Democratic and Labour Party (SDLP), held their seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] The unionist Democratic Unionist Party (DUP) and Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) (the latter in an electoral pact with the Conservatives), lost one seat each.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] This left the nationalist parties unchanged with eight seats, the main unionist parties with eight seats (all DUP), the Alliance with one seat and an independent unionist with one seat.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p01] It is the first time since the partition of Ireland that unionist parties failed to secure a majority of Northern Ireland's Westminster seats in a general election, and also the first time Sinn Féin obtained the largest share of the vote in Northern Ireland at a general election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The election resulted in an increase in the number of MPs from ethnic minorities from 14 to 27, including the first black and Asian female Conservative MPs, Helen Grant and Priti Patel, and the first female Muslim MPs, Rushanara Ali, Shabana Mahmood and Yasmin Qureshi.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] This means that 4.2% of MPs are from an ethnic minority – in the 2001 Census, it was reported that ethnic minorities comprised 7.9% of the population.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The number of female MPs rose to 141, an increase from 19.5% to 21.7% of all MPs, and the highest ever total; the number of female Conservative MPs rose from 18 (8.6% of all Conservatives) to 48 (15.7%).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In Northern Ireland a swing of more than 20% resulted in DUP First Minister Peter Robinson losing his Belfast East seat to the Alliance Party's Naomi Long, giving Alliance its first elected MP in Westminster.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Sir Reg Empey, leader of the UUP/Conservative alliance (UCUNF), standing for the first time in South Antrim, lost to the DUP incumbent William McCrea.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Thus both leaders of the main Unionist parties failed to win seats while the UUP for the first time had no MPs at Westminster.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] A few days after the election, Empey announced that he would resign before the party conference, triggering a leadership election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Sylvia Hermon, Lady Hermon retained her seat in North Down, significantly increasing her percentage of the vote despite a slightly lower turnout and her defection from the UUP/Conservative alliance to stand as an independent.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] New SDLP leader Margaret Ritchie, succeeding Eddie McGrady MP, won against Sinn Féin's Caitriona Ruane in South Down.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] All of the Sinn Féin and SDLP incumbents held their seats, although Sinn Féin's Michelle Gildernew retained her seat in Fermanagh & South Tyrone by only four votes over the Independent Unionist Unity candidate, Rodney Connor, after three recounts.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Many of the MPs who were most prominently caught up in the scandal decided, or were ordered not to stand for re-election in 2010.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Among them were Margaret Moran, Elliot Morley, David Chaytor, Nicholas and Ann Winterton, Derek Conway, John Gummer, Douglas Hogg, Anthony Steen, Peter Viggers, Julie Kirkbride and her husband Andrew MacKay.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Where sitting MPs did stand for re-election after their expenses claims were criticised, there were some notable losses.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Former Home Secretary Jacqui Smith lost her marginal Redditch seat, which showed a large 9.2% swing to the Conservatives.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Former Home Office minister Tony McNulty lost Harrow East to the Conservatives on an 8% swing, after repaying over £13,000 claimed on a second home, occupied by his parents, which was 8 miles away from his primary residence.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Ann Keen lost Brentford and Isleworth on a 6% swing, but her husband Alan Keen retained Feltham and Heston.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The couple were criticised for claiming for a second home in central London while rarely staying in their nearby constituency home.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Shahid Malik lost his Dewsbury seat on a 5.9% swing to the Conservatives.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Malik had been required to repay some of his expense claims and, at the time of the election, was under investigation for other claims.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] David Heathcoat-Amory was one of only two sitting Conservatives to be defeated when he lost Wells to the Liberal Democrats by 800 votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Heathcoat-Amory was criticised for claiming manure on expenses.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Phil Hope, who repaid over £40,000 in expenses, was defeated in his Corby constituency although the swing was lower than the national average at 3.3%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Hazel Blears, who had paid more than £13,000 to cover capital gains tax which she had avoided by "flipping" the designation of her main residence, suffered a large drop in her vote in Salford and Eccles, but was still comfortably re-elected; a 'Hazel must go' candidate won only 1.8%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Conversely, Brian Jenkins lost his Tamworth seat on a large 9.5% swing despite being described as a "saint" by *The Daily Telegraph* on account of his low expenses.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Ironically, his successor in the seat was Conservative Chris Pincher, whose future sexual assault scandal would bring down the premiership of Prime Minister Boris Johnson twelve years later.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Predictions of a rise in the number of successful Independents in the election as a result of the 2009 expenses scandal failed to materialise.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Broadcaster Esther Rantzen gathered a great deal of publicity for her campaign in Luton South constituency where the former MP Margaret Moran had stood down, but ended up losing her deposit in 4th place with 4.4% of the vote; the winner was Moran's successor as Labour candidate.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] There was also a high-profile campaign over expenses directed against Speaker John Bercow, who had 'flipped' his designation of second home.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] An imperfectly observed convention states that the major parties do not oppose the Speaker seeking re-election; Bercow faced two main opponents in Buckingham.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Independent former Member of the European Parliament John Stevens, standing on the Buckinghamshire Campaign for Democracy ticket, campaigned with a man dressed in a dolphin costume whom he called 'Flipper' and polled second with 21.4%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Former leader of the UK Independence Party Nigel Farage also fought the seat but came third in the vote with 17.4%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Problems occurred with voting at 27 polling places in 16 constituencies, and affected approximately 1,200 people.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] This situation was condemned by politicians of various parties.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Jenny Watson, chair of the Electoral Commission, the independent body that oversees the electoral process, was forced on to television to defend preparations and procedures.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] The Electoral Commission announced it would be carrying out a "thorough investigation".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Under the law in force at the 2010 election, voters had to have been handed their ballots by the 10 pm deadline; people who were waiting in queues to vote at 10 pm were not allowed to vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Some dissatisfied voters staged sit-ins to protest against what some of them had called "disenfranchisement".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In Liverpool, higher-than-expected turnout meant several polling stations ran out of ballot papers, with defeated council leader Warren Bradley stating that some residents were unable to cast their votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In Wyre and Preston North, a 14-year-old boy cast a vote after being sent a polling card.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In parts of Liberal Democrat leader Nick Clegg's Sheffield Hallam seat it was reported that students from the city's two universities were placed in separate queues from 'local' residents, who were given priority, resulting in many students being unable to cast their votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] When it became clear that no party would achieve an overall majority, the three main party leaders made public statements offering to discuss the options for forming the next government with the other parties.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Prior to the election, Nick Clegg and Menzies Campbell had continued the position of Charles Kennedy of not being prepared to form a coalition with either main party and of voting against any Queen's Speech unless there was an unambiguous commitment in it to introduce proportional representation.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] However, following the election results, Clegg shifted this position, arguing that the UK faced a 'fluid political situation' in the context of the first hung parliament in 36 years, and an urgent need for economic recovery following the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] He maintained that political leaders had a responsibility to act in the 'national interest' to provide a strong and stable government rather than pursuing narrow party gains.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Negotiations with the Labour Party were attempted but failed.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Clegg concluded that a stable coalition with Labour was impossible due to internal Labour Party revolts and the fact that even a combined Lib Dem – Labour bloc would still require the support of several smaller parties to reach a majority.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] In addition, prior to the election, Clegg had stated that the party with the most votes and seats should have the 'first right' to seek to form a government.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Since the Conservative Party won the most seats (306) and the highest share of the popular vote, Clegg felt a 'democratic' obligation to negotiate with them first.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Whilst the Conservatives refused to grant full proportional representation, they offered a referendum on the Alternative Vote (AV) system.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Clegg accepted this as a compromise that would at least 'repair the political system' and provide a stepping stone toward broader reform.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] On Wednesday 12 May, the two coalition parties jointly published the Conservative – Liberal Democrat coalition agreement.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] UK parties spent £31.1m on the campaign of which Conservatives spent 53%, the Labour Party spent 25% and the Liberal Democrats 15%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2010-united-kingdom-general-election-p02] Figures from returning officers show that the average administration cost per constituency was £173,846 meaning the average cost per vote was £3.81.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The **United Kingdom Alternative Vote referendum**, also known as the **UK-wide referendum on the Parliamentary voting system**, was held on Thursday 5 May 2011 in the United Kingdom to choose the method of electing MPs at subsequent general elections.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] It occurred as a provision of the Conservative–Liberal Democrat coalition agreement drawn up in 2010 (after a general election that had resulted in the first hung parliament since February 1974) and also indirectly in the aftermath of the 2009 expenses scandal.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] It operated under the provisions of the Parliamentary Voting System and Constituencies Act 2011 and was the first national referendum to be held under provisions laid out in the Political Parties, Elections and Referendums Act 2000.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Many local elections were also held on this day.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The referendum concerned whether to replace the present "first-past-the-post" system with the "alternative vote" (AV) method and was the first national referendum to be held across the whole of the United Kingdom in the 21st century.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The proposal to introduce AV was rejected by 67.9% of voters on a national turnout of 42%.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The failure of the referendum was considered a humiliating setback for Liberal Democrat leader Nick Clegg, who had acquiesced to the Conservative offer of a referendum on AV rather than proportional representation (PR) as part of the coalition agreement.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The referendum was linked to the ongoing decline of his popularity and that of the Liberal Democrats in general.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] This was only the second UK-wide referendum to be held (the first was the EC referendum in 1975) and the first of such to be overseen by the Electoral Commission.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] It is to date the only UK-wide referendum to be held on an issue not related to the European Communities or the European Union, and is also the first to have been not merely consultative: it committed the government to give effect to its decision.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] All registered electors over 18 (British, Irish and Commonwealth citizens living in the UK and enrolled British citizens living outside) – including members of the House of Lords (who cannot vote in UK general elections) – were entitled to take part.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] On a turnout of 42.2 percent, 68 percent voted "No" and 32 percent voted "Yes".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Ten of the 440 local voting areas recorded "Yes" votes above 50 per cent: four were Oxford, Cambridge, Edinburgh Central and Glasgow Kelvin, with the remaining six being in London.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The alternative vote and the single transferable vote (STV) for the House of Commons were debated in Parliament several times between 1917 and 1931, and came close to being adopted.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Both the Liberals and Labour at various times supported a change from non-transferable voting to AV or STV in one-, two- and three-member constituencies.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] STV was adopted for university seats (which were abolished in 1949).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Both AV and STV involve voters rank-ordering preferences and using ranked votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] However, STV uses multi-member constituencies and is considered to be a form of proportional representation, while AV uses single-member constituencies and is not a form of PR.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] In 1950, all constituencies became single-member and all votes non-transferable.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Other voting systems were introduced for various other British elections.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] STV was reintroduced in Northern Ireland and list-PR introduced for European elections except in Northern Ireland.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Whilst out of power, the Labour Party set up a working group to examine electoral reform.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The resulting Plant Commission reported in 1993 and recommended the adoption, for elections to the Commons, of the supplementary vote, the system used to elect the Mayor of London.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Labour's 1997 manifesto committed the party to a referendum on the voting system for the Commons and to setting up an independent commission to recommend a proportional alternative to FPTP to be put in that referendum.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] After winning the 1997 general election, the new Labour government consequently set up the Jenkins Commission into electoral reform, supported by the Liberal Democrats, the third party in British politics in recent years and long supporters of proportional representation.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] (The Commission chair, Roy Jenkins, was a Liberal Democrat peer and former Labour minister.) The commission reported in September 1998 and proposed the novel alternative vote top-up or AV+ system.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Having been tasked to meet a "requirement for broad proportionality", the Commission rejected both FPTP, as the status quo, and AV as options.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] It pointed out (chapter 3, para 21) that "the single-member constituency is not an inherent part of the British parliamentary tradition.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] It was unusual until 1885...Until [then] most seats [districts] were two-member..." (referring to the English system established in 1276).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Jenkins rejected AV because "so far from doing much to relieve disproportionality, it is capable of substantially adding to it".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] AV was also described as "disturbingly unpredictable" and "unacceptably unfair".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] However, legislation for a referendum was not put forward.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Proportional systems were introduced for the new Scottish Parliament and Welsh and London Assemblies, and the supplementary vote was introduced for mayoral elections.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] With House of Lords reform in 1999, AV was introduced to elect replacements for the remaining 92 hereditary peers who sit in the Lords.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] At the next general election in 2001, Labour's manifesto stated that the party would review the experience of the new systems (in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland) and the Jenkins report, to assess the possibility of changes to the Commons, which would still be subject to a referendum.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Electoral reform in the Commons remained at a standstill, although in the Scottish Parliament, a coalition of Labour and the Liberal Democrats introduced STV for local elections in Scotland.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] A Liberal Democrat amendment to hold the referendum earlier, and on STV, was defeated by 476 votes to 69.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] There was insufficient time remaining in the term of that Parliament for the Bill to become law before Parliament was dissolved; and so the move was dismissed by several Conservative and Liberal Democrat MPs as a political manoeuvre.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] In the ensuing 2010 general election campaign, the Labour manifesto supported the introduction of AV via a referendum, to "ensure that every MP is supported by the majority of their constituents voting at each election".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Liberal Democrats argued for proportional representation, preferably by single transferable vote, and the Conservatives argued for the retention of FPTP.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Both the Conservatives and Liberal Democrats proposed reducing the number of MPs, while the Conservative Party argued for more equal sized constituencies.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The 2010 UK general election held on 6 May resulted in a hung parliament, the first since 1974, leading to a period of negotiations.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Honouring a pre-election pledge, the Liberal Democrat leader Nick Clegg entered into negotiations with the Conservatives as the party who had won most votes and most seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] William Hague offered the Liberal Democrats a referendum on the alternative vote as part of a "final offer" in the Conservatives' negotiations for a proposed "full and proper" coalition between the two parties.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Hague and Conservative leader David Cameron said that this was in response to Labour offering the Liberal Democrats the alternative vote without a referendum, although it later emerged that Labour had not made such an offer.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Negotiations between the Liberal Democrats and Labour quickly ended.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] On 11 May 2010, Prime Minister Gordon Brown stepped down, followed by the establishment of a full coalition government between the Conservatives and Liberal Democrats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] David Cameron became Prime Minister and Liberal Democrat leader Nick Clegg became Deputy Prime Minister.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The initial Conservative–Liberal Democrat coalition agreement, dated 11 May 2010, detailed the issues which had been agreed between the two parties before they committed to entering into coalition.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Lords can only delay, rather than block, a Bill passed by the Commons.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] According to *The Guardian*, reporting after the Queen's Speech, unnamed pro-referendum Cabinet members were believed to want the referendum held on 5 May 2011, to coincide with elections to the Scottish parliament, the Welsh assembly and many English local councils.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Nick Clegg's prior hope of a referendum as early as October 2010 was considered unrealistic due to the parliamentary programme announced in the speech.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] On 5 July 2010, Clegg announced the detailed plans for the Parliamentary Reform Bill in a statement to the House of Commons, as part of the wider package of voting and election reforms set out in the coalition agreement, including setting the referendum date as 5 May 2011.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The plans to hold the vote on 5 May faced criticism from some Conservative MPs as distorting the result because turnout was predicted to be higher in those places where local elections were also held.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Clegg defended the date, stating the referendum question was simple and that it would save £17m in costs.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Over 45 MPs, mostly Conservatives, signed a motion calling for the date to be moved.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Bill contained the text of a proposed referendum question.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] permitting a simple **YES** / **NO** answer (to be marked with a single (X)).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] This wording was criticised by the Electoral Commission, saying that "particularly those with lower levels of education or literacy, found the question hard work and did not understand it".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Electoral Commission recommended a changed wording to make the issue easier to understand, and the government subsequently amended the Bill to bring it into line with the Electoral Commission's recommendations.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Bill passed an interim vote in the Commons on 7 September 2010 by 328 votes to 269.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] An amendment proposed in the Lords by Lord Rooker (Independent) to require a minimum turn-out of 40% for the referendum to be valid was supported by Labour, a majority of cross-benchers and ten rebel Conservatives, and was passed by one vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] In the latter hours of debate, a "game" of parliamentary ping-pong saw the Commons overturning the threshold amendment before it was reimposed by the Lords, and then removed again.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] After some compromises between the two Houses on amendments, the Bill was passed into law on 16 February 2011.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Parliamentary Voting System and Constituencies Act 2011 provides for the holding of the referendum, and the related changes had it led to the adoption of AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Passing the bill into law was a necessary measure before the referendum could actually take place.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] It received Royal assent on 16 February 2011.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Based on the coalition agreement, the referendum was a simple majority yes/no question as to whether to replace the current first-past-the-post (FPTP) electoral system used in general elections with the alternative vote (AV) system.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The referendum took place on 5 May 2011, coinciding with various United Kingdom local elections, the 2011 Scottish Parliament election, the 2011 Welsh Assembly election and the 2011 Northern Ireland Assembly election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The deadline for voters in England, Wales and Northern Ireland to register to vote in the referendum was midnight on Thursday 14 April 2011, whilst voters in Scotland had until midnight on Friday 15 April 2011 to register.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Anyone in the United Kingdom who qualified as an anonymous elector had until midnight on Tuesday 26 April 2011 to register.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] In the vote count, the referendum ballots in England, Scotland and Wales were counted after the various election ballots, from 4 pm on 6 May 2011.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The referendum had no minimum threshold on the required turnout needed for the result to be valid.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Anyone on the electoral register and eligible to vote in a general election was entitled to vote in the referendum.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] This includes British citizens living outside the UK who were registered as overseas electors.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] In addition, Members of the House of Lords, who are not eligible to vote in a general election, were entitled to vote in the referendum, provided they were entitled to vote in local elections or European Parliamentary elections.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The coalition partners campaigned on opposite sides, with the Liberal Democrats supporting AV and the Conservatives opposing it.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Despite the Conservative Party's formal position, party members who were aligned to the Conservative Action for Electoral Reform, an internal party group in favour of electoral reform, campaigned in favour, while a BBC News report described "some Tory MPs" as being "relaxed" about a "Yes" result.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Some Conservatives campaigned in favour of AV, *e.g.* Andrew Boff AM; and Andrew Marshall, former head of the Conservative Group on Camden Council.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Conservative Party uses a system of successive ballots to elect its leader, which has been described as a "form of AV" (since the candidate with the fewest votes is eliminated in each round), but unlike AV, the candidates are not ranked in order of preference during each ballot.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Labour elected a new leader following the 2010 general election and many of the leadership candidates supported AV, including winner Ed Miliband; however, Andy Burnham was critical of the referendum.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Former interim Labour Leader Margaret Beckett was president of the No to AV campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Other supporters of the party also used the referendum to attack the coalition and voiced opposition to the bill currently providing for the referendum, on the grounds of the inclusion of boundary changes that are viewed as beneficial to the Conservative Party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Plaid Cymru supported AV, but did not take an active role in the campaign, as it focused on separate Welsh votes on the same day.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Scottish National Party, while maintaining its longstanding support for PR-STV, also supported a "Yes" vote in the referendum.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Both of these parties opposed the planned referendum date, as they did not want it held at the same time as the 2011 Welsh Assembly elections and the 2011 Scottish Parliament elections respectively.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Among the Northern Irish parties, the Alliance Party and the Social Democratic and Labour Party (SDLP) supported AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] SDLP leader Margaret Ritchie announced that her party would actively campaign in favour.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Sinn Féin also supported a "Yes" vote, but the Democratic Unionist Party supported a "No" vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Green Party of England and Wales voted in favour of joining the campaign for AV in the referendum at its September 2010 party conference.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Many leading figures in the party supported the change as a step towards their preferred system, proportional representation.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Previously, the party's leader and only MP, Caroline Lucas, had called for a referendum that included a choice of proportional representation.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The UK Independence Party's National Executive Committee formally announced that it would be supporting Alternative Vote, although it would prefer a proportional system.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] An e-mail was sent to members informing them that they might vote against AV, but were not allowed to campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The British National Party criticised AV and supported a "No" vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Respect Party also supported proportional representation and campaigned against AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Rob Hoveman, on behalf of Tower Hamlets Respect, wrote to the *East London Advertiser* on 24 February 2011 urging a "No" vote on the grounds that the AV system created an even greater imbalance between votes and seats, and urging a proportional system instead.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Scottish Green Party also supported AV, although it prefers the adoption of STV for all elections.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Ulster Unionist Party and Traditional Unionist Voice supported a "No" vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Green Party Northern Ireland also opposed the change to AV, as they viewed it as a betrayal of proportional representation.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The English Democrats, the Christian Peoples Alliance and the Christian Party all supported AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Pirate Party UK endorsed a "Yes" vote, with over 90% of members expressing support for AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Liberal Party agreed to support the "Yes" campaign, seeing AV as "a potential 'stepping stone' to further reform" and STV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Communist Party of Britain opposed AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Mebyon Kernow, the Cornish nationalist party, favoured proportional representation and was disappointed that the referendum did not give voters that option.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] However, leader Dick Cole announced on 1 April 2011 that Mebyon Kernow would be supporting the "Yes" campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The United Kingdom Libertarian Party favoured AV as a slight improvement on first-past-the-post.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Socialist Party of Great Britain adopted a neutral position, arguing "what matters more is what we use our votes for" in the context of class struggle.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Socialist Party opposed AV, pointing out that it is not more proportional than First Past the Post.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Alliance for Workers' Liberty opposed AV, arguing that it did not offer progress on the party's main democratic demands.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Prime Minister David Cameron of the Conservative Party and Deputy Prime Minister Nick Clegg of the Liberal Democrats made speeches backing the "No" and "Yes" campaigns respectively on the same day, but were thereafter not expected to take much part in the campaigns, although both were active since.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Cameron described AV as "undemocratic, obscure, unfair and crazy".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] He was praised for his intervention by back-bench Conservative MPs.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Labour leader Ed Miliband said he would take an active part in the "Yes" campaign, while Wales's First Minister and Welsh Labour Leader Carwyn Jones and Scottish Labour Leader Iain Gray both also supported AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Also supporting the "Yes" campaign were over 50 Labour MPs including Alan Johnson, Peter Hain, Hilary Benn, John Denham, Liam Byrne, Sadiq Khan, Tessa Jowell, Ben Bradshaw, Douglas Alexander, Alistair Darling, Diane Abbott and Debbie Abrahams.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Liberal Democrats supported a "Yes" vote and many individual Liberal Democrat politicians were active in the "Yes" campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The SNP leader, Alex Salmond, supported a "Yes" vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] UKIP supported a "Yes" vote and their principal spokesmen on the campaign were William Dartmouth MEP and party leader, Nigel Farage MEP.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The Conservative Party announced that seven MPs (Conor Burns, George Eustice, Sam Gyimah, Kwasi Kwarteng, Charlotte Leslie, Priti Patel, Chris Skidmore) and two former candidates (Chris Philp and Maggie Throup, later elected as MPs) would act as party spokespersons in the "No" campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Overall, most Labour MPs supported the "No" campaign rather than the "Yes" campaign, with other notable opponents of AV including Paul Goggins, Ann Clwyd, Sir Gerald Kaufman, Austin Mitchell, Margaret Hodge, Lindsay Hoyle, Jim Fitzpatrick, Dennis Skinner and Keith Vaz.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Also supporting a "No" vote were crossbencher and former SDP leader Lord Owen, who supported the No to AV But Yes to PR campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Conservative politician Michael Gove was initially mistakenly announced by the No to AV campaign as opposing AV, but his advisers stated that he had never been involved in the campaign and had not yet made up his mind.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Over five Labour MPs announced as opposing AV were also found to have been wrongly included: for example, Alun Michael supported a "Yes" vote, while Meg Hillier did not lend her name to either campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Some Conservative politicians did support AV, including John Strafford, a former member of the Conservative Party's national executive, who chaired the Conservative campaign in favour of a "Yes" vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Two campaign groups were established in response to the proposed referendum, one on each side of the debate.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] NOtoAV was established to campaign against the change to the alternative vote and YES!
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] To Fairer Votes was established to campaign in favour.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Take Back Parliament, the Electoral Reform Society, Make My Vote Count, and Unlock Democracy all campaigned in favour of the change to AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] It provided "substantial" sums of money to the "No" campaign and marshalled its members to vote "No".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Unions generally supported the "No" campaign, with only Billy Hayes, general secretary of the Communication Workers' Union, supporting AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Compass supported the change to the AV and urged the Labour Party to do so too.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] It prefers a switch to a more proportional system, but viewed AV as superior to FPTP.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] ResPublica supported the change to AV and urged the Conservative Party to do so too.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Policy Exchange opposed the change to AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] A report by the Institute for Public Policy Research in January 2011 was very critical of FPTP's flaws, while a report in April 2011 came down in support of AV over FPTP.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] However, the IPPR also previously called for a wider choice in the referendum and favours Alternative Vote Plus over FPTP or AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] A number of academics entered the debate, either in mainstream media or through blogs, social networking or academic publication.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Those in favour of AV included Timothy Gowers (Cambridge), David Held (LSE), Patrick Dunleavy (LSE), and Helen Margetts (Oxford), Thom Brooks (Newcastle University), Alastair McMillan (Sheffield), and Ben Saunders (Stirling).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Dan Felsenthal (LSE) criticised AV as "deeply flawed", though he also described it as "a minor improvement on the current first-past-the-post system".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Moon (Sheffield) argued that AV would be worse than FPTP, though he regarded both as flawed and supported a move to proportional representation.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] At a Voting Power in Practice workshop, held at the Chateau du Baffy, in France from 30 July to 2 August 2010, 22 voting theory specialists voted to select the "best voting procedure" to elect a candidate from a selection of three or more.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] First past the post received no votes, compared to 10 for AV, although another system, Approval Voting (not on offer in the referendum), received 15 votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] On 11 March, 29 historians, including Niall Ferguson, Simon Sebag Montefiore, Andrew Roberts and David Starkey, wrote to *The Times* expressing opposition to the adoption of the Alternative Vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Greenpeace and Friends of the Earth support the Yes!
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] To Fairer Votes campaign, as do the Joseph Rowntree Reform Trust, Operation Black Vote, the New Economics Foundation, 38 Degrees and bassac.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Educational trust The Constitution Society has also worked to increase public awareness of the issues involved in the debate.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] AV was also supported by Kevin Maguire, associate editor of the *Daily Mirror* newspaper, and journalist Polly Toynbee.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Comedian and actor Steve Coogan also supported a "Yes" vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Supporting a "No" vote were television presenter Esther Rantzen, scientist and Labour peer Lord Winston; nightclub impresario Peter Stringfellow, cricketers David Gower and Darren Gough, Olympic rower James Cracknell and F1 boss Sir Frank Williams.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Actor and television presenter Ross Kemp also backed the "No" campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Jonathan Bartley (founder and co-director of the Ekklesia religious thinktank, and who was later co-leader of the Green Party) supported the referendum.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] Anti-corruption campaigner, former broadcaster and independent MP, Martin Bell supported AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] By around the beginning of May, the "Yes" campaign had spent £3.4 million compared to £2.6 million by the "No" campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The "Yes" campaign revealed that it had raised £2 million (as of 15 February 2011), with 95% coming from two donors, the Electoral Reform Society and the Joseph Rowntree Reform Trust.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The "Yes" campaign also received five-figure sums from Alan Parker, who is close to both Gordon Brown and David Cameron, and Paul Marshall, a donor to the Liberal Democrats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] There were initially accusations in the press that the "No" campaign was refusing to publish details of their donors and the "Yes" campaign was quicker than the "No" campaign in doing this, but subsequently said on 18 February 2011 they would do so before the referendum date.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] However, they had not done so by 28 March 2011 when the "Yes" campaign published an updated list of all donors of over £7,500, and launched a petition calling on the "No" campaign to do the same.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The "No" campaign released a list of donors on 9 April 2011, which included several major donors to the Conservative Party, including Lord (John) Sainsbury, Michael Farmer, Lord Harris, Lord Fink and Lord Edmiston.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] In total, the "No" campaign had raised by that date £1.8m in donations of over the declarable limit of £7,500 from 41 donors, with the largest being from billionaire Peter Cruddas, founder of the CMC spread betting firm, who gave £400,000.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The *Guardian* newspaper identified 42 of the 53 named donors to the "No" campaign as donors to the Conservative Party, while one, the GMB union, is a donor to the Labour Party, and nine were not identified in official donor records.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The remaining donor is official funding from the electoral commission.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] The donors include seven Conservative peers.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] They quote Margaret Beckett, a leading Labour "No" campaigner, as saying this situation is a "necessary evil".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] While the "Yes" campaign released figures of all donations over the declarable limit after it was set up, the "No" campaign did not declare any donations prior to the referendum bill receiving Royal assent, for it was not required to do under the relevant regulations.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p01] David Blunkett, a "No" campaigner, called on the "No" campaign to do so.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The initial part of the campaign was overshadowed by continuing Parliamentary battles over the introducing Bill, which had threatened to delay the referendum date.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Launching their campaign, supporters of AV argued that the need for candidates to campaign for later preferences would encourage candidates to appeal to a broader cross-section of the electorate.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] They also pointed out the declining number of people voting for the main two parties in the UK over recent decades.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The "Yes" campaign sought to present its campaign as being on behalf of members of the public.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The "No" campaign sought to play on the unpopularity of the leader of the Liberal Democrats, Nick Clegg, and to present the referendum as an opportunity to punish Clegg at the polls.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] It also claimed that Clegg described AV as "a miserable little compromise" before the 2010 general election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The fuller quote says: "I am not going to settle for a miserable little compromise thrashed out by the Labour Party." However, the Conservatives rejected the possibility of introducing PR in coalition negotiations, leading to a referendum in which the choice was between FPTP and AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] While officially supporting a "No" vote, the Conservative Party leadership reportedly initially held back on campaigning and advised major Conservative Party donors not to donate to the "No" campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] However, this position changed in January 2011 and the leadership became more involved, with requests to donors to fund the "No" campaign and staff and party headquarters becoming directly involved in campaigning.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] In mid-February, the prime minister, David Cameron, and the deputy prime minister, Nick Clegg, made opposing speeches advocating a "No" and "Yes" result respectively.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Clegg argued that AV would mean "fairer votes" and that FPTP produced more safe seats, and linked these to the MPs' expenses scandal.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] He said that AV would encourage politicians to work to appeal to more of the electorate rather than just their core supporters.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Cameron, in contrast, argued that FPTP delivers more accountability, and claimed it reduces the number of hung parliaments.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] He insisted that "when it comes to our democracy, Britain shouldn't have to settle for anyone's second choice." He also claimed, on BBC Radio 4's *Today* programme on 3 May 2011, that AV would undermine the fundamental principle of "one person, one vote".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Despite the coalition parties being on different sides in the campaign, Cameron insisted that "whatever the result", the coalition would continue.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Caroline Lucas, head of the Green Party of England and Wales said in support of AV that "they can vote for what they believe in and I think that will be very liberating for a lot of people".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The "No" campaign launched with a claim that choosing AV would cost £250 million.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] However, this figure was criticised on several grounds.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] For example, it included an estimated £82 million for holding the referendum, that would have applied whatever the referendum outcome, and failed to take into account costs saved from holding the referendum at the same time as other elections.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The £250 million figure also included £130 million for the cost of electronic voting systems, although these were not used by the largest country then using AV, Australia, and there were no plans to use such machines if AV were introduced in the UK.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Labour MP Douglas Alexander described the figure claimed as a "lie".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] A *Channel 4 News* Fact Check concluded that the specific claim that AV would require electronic counting machines, the main component of the £250 million figure, was "fiction".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The Treasury stated that the adoption of AV would not lead to any spending cuts.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The "No" campaign launched a series of advertisements on posters and in regional newspapers based on the £250 million figure.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The "Yes" campaign described these as "shameful", a "smear" and "lies", and complained to the Electoral Commission and Advertising Standards Authority, both of whom stated that they did not have powers to regulate individual adverts in the campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] On 5 May, David Blunkett, one of the Labour Party former-government ministers who had supported the "No" campaign, admitted that the £250 million figure used by the "No" campaign had been fabricated, and that the "No" campaign had knowingly lied about the figure and other claims during the campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Paddy Ashdown pointed out that in the twentieth century Australia had fewer hung Parliaments under AV than the UK had under FPTP.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Under AV each voter casts a single transferable vote or ranked vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The "No" campaign argued that some would get multiple votes under AV, and that the system was therefore contrary to the principle of "one person, one vote" (which they adopted as a slogan of their campaign).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] This argument was heavily criticised by Ipsos MORI, Channel Four News Fact Check, and many academic commentators.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The FullFact site stated "some of these claims have trod a fine line between accuracy and error".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The "Yes" campaign argued that AV would be fairer, and that it would reduce or even eliminate 'safe seats', making MPs work harder.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] This was contested by the "No" campaign, again with reference to Australia.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] This view was supported by Alan Renwick, who stated that "AV wouldn't significantly change the number of safe seats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The Foundation found that, with FPTP, the average number of seats changing hands per election was 13% and this could rise to 16% under AV, modestly increasing voter power overall, but concluded "that neither system is very good at translating votes into electoral power".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The "Yes" campaign argued that AV would ensure that every MP was supported by an overall majority, more than 50% of the voters.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] However, in its Guide to AV, Ipsos MORI stated "this is not really true, but maybe it's a defensible simplification".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] AV ensures that a candidate is elected with the support of at least 50% of voters who have expressed a preference between the final two candidates in the contest.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] If some voters have indicated that they are indifferent between the final two, by not ranking either of them on the ballot paper, then the winner may be elected with the support of fewer than 50% of all votes cast.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Rawlings and Thrasher stated that "the claims that AV will guarantee local majority support can only be validated if every voter is compelled or chooses to cast a full range of preferences.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] In the most recent general election, roughly two-thirds of MPs had been elected without an overall majority.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Rawlings and Thrasher predicted that "more than four out of ten" MPs would still not have majority support under AV, while Ipsos MORI stated "It is certainly true that in many constituencies ...
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] MPs elected under AV will have the support of a higher proportion of voters than they did under FPTP".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The "No" campaign argued that only three countries use AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] It also stated that the Australian public wish to do away with AV, although this claim has been contested by ABC elections analyst Antony Green.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] At the time of the referendum, three nations used AV for parliamentary elections: Australia, Papua New Guinea, and Fiji.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] However, AV is also used internationally for many other forms of election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] AV is used for Irish presidential elections and for by-elections in the Republic of Ireland, and in some local elections in New Zealand.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] In the United Kingdom, AV is used by MPs to elect the chairs of select committees, the Speaker of the House of Lords, and the Deputy Speakers of the House of Commons.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] AV is also used in by-elections to select hereditary peers for the House of Lords.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] A variant of AV called the supplementary vote was at the time used to elect the Mayor of London and the mayors of other UK cities.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] A related system called the exhaustive ballot is used to elect the Speaker of the House of Commons.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] AV is used for various elections in the United States (see AV in the United States).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] AV is used by many private organisations in the UK, for example in the leadership elections of the Labour Party and the Liberal Democrats.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] AV is also used by the Royal British Legion, and in certain trade unions and students' unions.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] In the US, AV is now used to decide the winner of the Oscar for Best Picture.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] A method similar to AV, called the two round system, is widely used internationally, although in that method voters only get one vote, and thus cannot rank options or have their votes transferred, and only the top two candidates move forward to the next round.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] For example, it is used to elect the National Assembly of France and the Presidents of eighty nations.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The United States also uses primaries, followed by a second round, for the President, House of Representatives and the Senate.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] It uses a preferential ballot like AV but is used for elections in multi-seat constituencies.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] It is used for national elections in the Republic of Ireland, Australia and Malta, for elections to the Northern Ireland Assembly, and for other purposes in many other nations.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The "No" campaign stressed that FPTP is used in over fifty countries, with a combined population of approximately 2.4 billion people.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] FPTP is used for legislature elections in the United States, India and Canada, as well as other non-G20 nations.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] It is used for presidential elections in twenty countries, and for various forms of election in 45 others (35 of these are Member states of the Commonwealth of Nations or British Overseas Territories).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Some opponents of AV saw it as a stepping stone toward unwanted (for them) proportional representation, while some supporters of proportional representation saw the referendum as a lost opportunity that would delay a move to proportional representation.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Both positions have been described as "entirely speculative".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] An *Evening Standard* editorial described the result of a "No" win: "the issue of electoral reform will be shelved for a generation".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Tactical voting means that a voter supports a candidate other than their sincere preference, in order to get a relatively desirable outcome.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] No conventional (i.e. ordinal) voting system can eliminate tactical voting (under the Gibbard–Satterthwaite theorem), and situations in which AV is susceptible to tactical voting can be demonstrated.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The Yes to AV campaign argued that, under AV, such scenarios were rare or theoretical.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The independent market research group Ipsos MORI has published a guide to AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] This states that the scenario in which tactical voting might influence the outcome of an AV election "is very easy to demonstrate in the case of AV and is unlikely to be especially rare".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] It is however true that, under AV, it is harder for the tactical voter to know what effect he is going to have so the prevalence of what is strictly defined as "tactical voting" may be reduced under AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] First-past-the-post is a monotonic voting system, while AV meets independence of clones and mutual majority criteria.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The British National Party (BNP) supported a "No" vote in the referendum.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] In response, Conservative chairman and "No" supporter Baroness Warsi described AV as "a system which rewards extremism and gives oxygen to extremist groups".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] In response, the "Yes" campaign launched advertising with the slogan, "Say No to the BNP, Say Yes on 5th May" pointing out the BNP's opposition to AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The final weeks of the campaign were marked by an increased rancour, with a battle of words between members of the Coalition government.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The "No" campaign countered, quoting a senior returning officer (Anthony Mayer), who said that voting machines would be essential with AV if results are desired as quickly as today, rather than counting over the weekend after a general election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] See the row over possible costs section for a fuller discussion.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Huhne was reported to have strongly criticised Conservative colleagues at a Cabinet meeting in early May 2011 for the "No" campaign's material.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] However, one of the key "No" campaign leaflets he targeted, showing a newborn baby with the slogan "She needs a maternity unit, not an alternative voting system", was developed by Dan Hodges, a Labour Party campaigner working for NO2AV.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] However, the "No" campaign responded by pointing out that a majority of Labour MPs opposed AV (130 out of 255 opposing AV, 86 in support).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] In the last week a grassroots campaign featuring Reform Cat in the YouTube video "Is your Cat confused about the referendum on the voting system on the 5th May?" which was released on 27 April 2011, gained more views than either official campaign videos.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Under the alternative vote system proposed in the referendum, voters would still be electing just one candidate associated with one geographic constituency.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Instead of simply voting for one candidate on the ballot paper (with an "X"), the voter would instead be asked to rank one or more of the candidates in order of preference.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] If after first preferences have been counted, no one candidate has a majority of the votes cast, then the bottom candidate will be eliminated and votes for that candidate are transferred to each voter's next available preference.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The process continues repeatedly until one candidate reaches a majority and wins.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The system proposed was a form of "optional preferential voting", in that voters would not be obliged to rank every candidate in order of preference in order to cast a valid vote.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] This was repealed by the Parliamentary Voting System and Constituencies Act 2011 (Repeal of Alternative Vote Provisions) Order 2011.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The referendum was held nationally across all four countries of the United Kingdom as a single majority vote in 440 voting areas and twelve regional count areas.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] In England the districts were used as the voting areas before being combined into the nine regional count areas.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] In Scotland the constituencies of the Scottish Parliament were the voting areas, and in Wales the voting areas were the constituencies of the National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland was a voting area.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The following table shows the breakdown of the voting areas for the referendum within the United Kingdom.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] According to the Electoral Commission, the votes were first counted in the 440 voting areas across the United Kingdom.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Except in Northern Ireland, the results from these local counts were relayed to twelve regional count areas to be officially announced by the regional counting officers.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Scotland and Wales were each classed as one regional count area, so votes in those areas were counted and declared locally within Scottish Parliament and Welsh Assembly constituency boundaries before the results were declared nationally.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Northern Ireland was also classed as a single regional count area but its votes were counted and declared nationally as one unit.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] In England, the votes were counted and declared locally at district council level, and those results were carried over to the nine remaining regional count areas.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] With a national turnout of 42% across the United Kingdom the target to secure the majority win for the winning side was 9,639,512 votes.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The decision by the electorate was a decisive "No" vote to adopting the alternative vote system in all future United Kingdom general elections by a majority of 6,860,516 votes over those who had voted "Yes" in favour of the proposal.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Ahead of the last results from Northern Ireland, the result was confirmed as a "No", as it was mathematically impossible for the "Yes" voters to outnumber them.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Further details of campaigning decisions emerged after the referendum result, with Dan Hodges reporting that the Conservatives had endorsed the "No" campaign's targeting of Nick Clegg, although they had originally opposed the idea.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Hodges also reported that an aide of David Cameron secretly met "No" campaign leaders in a hotel room in order to stop the Liberal Democrats finding out the scale of Conservative involvement.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The Coalition government continued and sought to present a united front after the fractious campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Former Conservative Cabinet minister Michael Portillo criticised Cameron, saying he "forgot the importance of courtesy" towards Clegg and the Liberal Democrats and, thus, the survival of the Coalition, when he joined what Portillo called "the disgraceful No campaign".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] On 8 July 2011, the alternative vote provisions were repealed, bringing the statutory process that had initiated the referendum to an end.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The decisive "No" vote continues to be cited as an endorsement of first-past-the-post and a rejection of proportional representation, despite the fact that AV alone is not a proportional system.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] Clegg, already unpopular for signing the coalition agreement with the Conservatives, saw his fortunes worsen.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The referendum was linked to the steep ongoing decline of his popularity and that of the Liberal Democrats in general.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/2011-united-kingdom-alternative-vote-referendum-p02] The party would go onto lose 49 seats in the 2015 general election, plummeting from 23% to just 8% of the total national vote share.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The **Communist Party of Britain** (**CPB**) is a communist party in Great Britain which emerged from a dispute between Eurocommunists and Marxist-Leninists in the Communist Party of Great Britain in 1988.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] It follows Marxist–Leninist theory and supports what it regards as existing socialist states.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party has fraternal relationships with the ruling parties in Cuba, China, Laos, and Vietnam.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] It is affiliated nationally to the Cuba Solidarity Campaign and the Venezuela Solidarity Campaign.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] It is a member of the International Meeting of Communist and Workers' Parties, together with 117 other political parties.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] After the fall of the Soviet Union, the party was one of two original British signatories to the Pyongyang Declaration.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The Communist Party of Britain was established in April 1988 by a disaffected section of the Communist Party of Great Britain (CPGB).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] This section sought to preserve the Communist Party, saving it from its forthcoming dissolution under a revisionist, Eurocommunist leadership.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In the period leading up to 1988, the Communist Party of Great Britain was in turmoil as the leadership fought the Marxist–Leninist tendencies inside the party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The rupture was made publicly visible in August/September 1982 after the CPGB's theoretical journal *Marxism Today* published a feature article by Tony Lane which was critical of the labour movement.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The CPGB-affiliated *Morning Star* newspaper responded with a front-page article by the party's Industrial Organiser Mick Costello criticising the *Marxism Today* article.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The CPGB's executive committee was flooded with communication from party branches over the affair.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party did not withdraw support for *Marxism Today*, but the editorial board did introduce a disclaimer that 'the views expressed by authors are personal and not necessarily those of the editor or editorial board', marking the journal's deviation from the party line.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Both publications came to characterise separate visions for the future of the party; the internal opposition rallied around the *Morning Star* and the reformist leadership around *Marxism Today*.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] These early signs of trouble attracted international attention, notably from the East German SED which was concerned about the Eurocommunist tendency in the CPGB.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] At the CPGB's 38th congress in November 1983, Tony Chater the editor of the *Morning Star*, as well as the assistant editor David Whitfield, were both removed from their positions on the party's executive.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] However, they were able to keep their positions at the paper, as it is owned and managed separately by the People's Press Printing Society co-operative.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The following year at the PPPS Annual General Meeting in June 1984, a majority of delegates re-elected Chater and Whitfield to the management committee of the newspaper, against the wishes of the CPGB leadership.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In November 1984, the North-West District Congress elected an opposition majority to its District Committee, to which the leadership responded by declaring the district election illegitimate.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] A similar movement was brewing in London, where the CPGB General Secretary Gordon McLennan pre-emptively dissolved the London District Congress and 11 members of the District Committee were suspended.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In Scotland, 20 branches were brought under disciplinary sanctions.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The CPGB Executive Committee then brought the dispute to a special congress on 18–20 May 1985, with a draft resolution condemning the *Morning Star* and the group around it.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Over 650 amendments were submitted to the resolution, which was eventually passed after a long debate, and followed up by the expulsion of eighteen members.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In June 1985, dissident and expelled members of the CPGB formed the Communist Campaign Group.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] This group declared itself loyal to the party programme, and stated its aim was to prevent the liquidation of the party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The Campaign Group was provided an office within the premises of the *Morning Star*.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The first post-congress meeting of the new CPGB Executive Committee in July 1985 dropped the commitment for party members to support the *Morning Star*; it concluded with the dissolution of more branches and further disciplinary measures, such as the expulsion of Ken Gill.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] From 1987, the CPB believed that the CPGB existed to promote reformism and class collaboration, while still defending Gorbachev's actions in the Soviet Union.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Kevin Halpin was invited to Moscow to discuss the possibility that the CPGB would break apart, he was advised by the CPSU that the Campaign Group should continue working within the existing party structures.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] On 8 January 1988 the Campaign Group called a press conference to announce the formation of the Communist Party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The re-establishment congress took place over the weekend of 23–24 April 1988, where one of the prominent leaders of the Campaign Group, Mike Hicks, was elected to the position of General Secretary.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The first party card was issued to Andrew Rothstein, who had also been one of the founding members of the CPGB.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The following year the leaders of the CPGB formally declared that they had abandoned its programme, *The British Road to Socialism*.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Many members perceived this as the party turning its back on socialism.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The CPGB dissolved itself in 1991 and reformed as the Democratic Left.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Many members of the Straight Left faction who had stayed in the CPGB formed a group called "Communist Liaison" which later opted to join the CPB.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Others remained in the Democratic Left or joined the Labour Party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party still has members who were active in the CPGB, some of whom were active in the Anti-Apartheid Movement and trade union disputes such as the Upper Clyde work-in or the miners' strike of 1984–1985.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In reaction to the Revolutions of 1989, the party initially denied that the uprising in the GDR was linked to socialism or German reunification.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] By Summer 1990, however, after the party's reporting of events in Romania and Czechoslovakia, they acknowledged that the people and communists in those areas had rejected socialism and the ruling communist parties.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] This had mixed reactions within the party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In 1998, Hicks was ousted as such in a 17–13 vote moved by John Haylett (who was also editor of the *Morning Star*) at a meeting of the party's executive committee.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Hicks' supporters on the Management Committee of the *Morning Star* responded by suspending and then sacking Haylett, which led to a prolonged strike at the *Morning Star*, ending in victory for Haylett and his reinstatement.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Some of Hicks' supporters were expelled and others resigned in protest.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] They formed a discussion group called Marxist Forum, which is now defunct.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Andrew Murray was a Communist Party member until late 2016.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Prior to the formation of the Respect – The Unity Coalition, with the support of the Socialist Workers Party, the party engaged in a debate about whether to join an electoral alliance with Respect and George Galloway.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Those in favour, including general secretary Rob Griffiths, Andrew Murray and *Morning Star* editor John Haylett, were, however, defeated at a Special Congress in 2004.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In 2009, the party was one of the founder organisations of the No2EU electoral alliance alongside the RMT and a number of other left parties.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The alliance stood in the 2009 and 2014 European Parliament elections on a platform of opposition to the European Union, which it considers undemocratic and neo-liberal.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In 2010, the party was part of "Unity for Peace and Socialism".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Later the party went on to lead a *Left Leave Campaign* (which was chaired by the party's General Secretary Robert Griffiths) along with the Socialist Workers Party, advocating the progressive case for a leave vote in the 2016 referendum on EU membership.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party was a founding member of the People's Assembly Against Austerity in 2013, along with a number of other political and campaign groups, to create a broad organisation in opposition to austerity policies of the major political parties of Britain and of the European Union.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The People's Charter, which the Communist Party had helped create several years earlier, was subsequently voted to be incorporated into the People's Assembly.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] At the 2017 general election, the party fielded no candidates and gave its support to the Labour Party under the leadership of Jeremy Corbyn.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The CPB said it was the first election at which neither it nor the CPGB had fielded any candidates.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In March 2018, Susan Michie, a leading member of the CPB, said that the party would no longer stand against Labour in general elections.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] CPB members should be "working full tilt" for the election of Corbyn as prime minister, she said.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In the 2019 general election, the party again fielded no candidates and gave its support to the Labour Party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] However following the resignation of Corbyn as leader of the Labour Party and the election of Keir Starmer as his successor, the CPB again decided to field candidates in elections.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In February 2021, the party's executive committee decided to mount one of the biggest electoral campaigns since the early 1980s.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In 2021, the party contested parliamentary seats in the Scottish parliamentary election, all regional lists in the Welsh Senedd election and seats across England in the May local elections.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party briefly had a Councillor on Barrow Borough Council, after he left the Labour Party in February 2023, until the council was abolished in April the same year.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In 2024, the party contested 14 parliamentary seats at the general election, the most it has fought since its formation in 1988.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In the 1987 election the CPGB, its predecessor, fielded candidates in 19 seats, and the CPB split from it the year after.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] It won none of the 14 seats fought in 2024 but won 2,622 votes, its best result at a general election.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party's ideology is Marxism–Leninism.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] It is anti-imperialist, anti-capitalist, pro-trade union and supports "progressive federalism".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party takes the traditional Marxist approach to capitalism, saying that it is at fault for wars, climate change, and corruption.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party believes that the First World War was a war between imperialists, caused by competition between monopolies.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] They criticise US imperialism, and US involvement in regime change.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] They also hold that the World Trade Organization, World Bank, International Monetary Fund and European Union work to push a neoliberal, imperialist agenda.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party claims that inequality in the UK can be traced back to capitalism, with workers providing the country with goods and not being properly paid for it, with workers' pay coming under pressure in the recent decades.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party's attitude towards the Soviet Union is positive, with criticism of Nikolai Yezhov's actions during the late 1930s as 'violations of socialist democracy'.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Both the party and the *Morning Star* approved of perestroika and processes of reform in the late 1980s, believing that these would pave the way to a more humane socialism.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The Communist Party of Britain and Workers' Party of Korea are both members of the International Meeting of Communist and Workers' Parties, and so have positive relations.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Thus, the Young Communist League has fraternal relations with the Socialist Patriotic Youth League.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] *Challenge*, the magazine of the YCL, have published articles in support of the DPRK.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] During the 2024 United Kingdom general election, J.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Rowling endorsed the party for its views on transgender issues, The Communist Party of Britain affirmed support for transgender rights in response.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In April 2025 the party and the Young Communist League both stated support for the Supreme Court ruling that a woman was defined by "biological sex" and affirmed the ruling's importance in creating safe spaces for women.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party has described the Russo-Ukrainian War as an "ongoing capitalist conflict".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] It criticises the banning of the Ukrainian Communist Party and demands the restoration of "democratic rights" in Ukraine, whilst also being critical of "US and Russian attempts to carve up Ukraine's rich natural recourses".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The Communist Party describes itself as a "disciplined and democratic organisation" and operates on a model of democratic centralism.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] These are normally localities (towns or counties, for example), although workplace branches also exist.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In England, branches are grouped into coherent geographical areas and send delegates to a biennial District Congress which elects a District Committee for its area.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Similarly, the Welsh and Scottish branches send delegates to their own national congresses where each elects an executive committee.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] These congresses also decide the broad perspectives for party activity within their districts and nations.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The all-Britain national congress is also held biennially.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Delegates from districts, nations and branches themselves decide the party's policy as a whole and elect an executive committee (EC) that carries out a presidium-like function, including decision-making and policy-formation whilst congress is not in session.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The EC also elects a Political Committee (PC) to provide leadership when the EC is not meeting.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The YCL is the autonomous youth group of the Communist Party, with its own internal organisation.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] It carries out work alongside the party, while maintaining its own branches, activities, and events such as an annual summer camp.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Young members of the party are automatically enrolled into the youth wing, however membership of both organisations is not synonymous, as it is possible to independently join the YCL without joining the party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The league, like its party, operates on a model of democratic centralism.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The Coordinating Committee is a bureau within the Communist Party which meets with communist parties that have significant memberships in Britain.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] These include parties from Bangladesh, Britain, Chile, Cyprus, Greece, Guyana, India, Iran, Iraq, Palestine and Sudan.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Under the Registration of Political Parties Act 1998, which regulated the use of symbols on ballot slips and electoral material, the Communist Party is the only British political party entitled to use a stand-alone hammer and sickle in such cases.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party tends to use the hammer and dove (adopted when the party was re-established in 1988) in conjunction with the hammer and sickle in publications and on other material, with the hammer and dove normally taking primacy.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Former members include Bob Crow of the RMT union, Ken Gill of the Manufacturing, Science and Finance (MSF) union, and Kate Hudson of the Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament (CND).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Current members include Susan Michie, a member of the UK Government's Scientific Advisory Group for Emergencies and Independent SAGE advising on behavioural science measures during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] From 2006 to 2014, the party held a membership of over 900 members.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In 2015, this figure dropped to below 800 members, although it has since recovered with growth in the Young Communist League.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In 2018, there were 915 members of the CPB and YCL combined, and by 2019 it had increased to 1,011 members, At the 56th party congress in 2021 it was reported that the party had grown to over 1,200 members.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] As of 2022, the party maintains branches in most major cities.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] General Secretary, Robert Griffiths said in 2017 that CPB is organised in "just about every part of Britain".
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] By December 2023 the party had grown to 1,308 members, along with 500 members of the YCL (some of whom also hold party membership).
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In July 2023, the party claimed via Twitter that it had a membership number not seen since the 1980s.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The statement of accounts submitted to the Electoral Commission in 2023 reported a total annual income of £171,755.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In order to join the party, applicants must pay a registration fee of £6.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] After this they will be contacted by the membership officer of their local branch to arrange an interview.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party publishes a wide variety of literature and material.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] A theoretical and discussion journal published on a quarterly basis.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The content of the journal covers book reviews, feature articles, letters and sometimes poetry.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The magazine of the Young Communist League.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] It mainly covers news, feature articles and political reports.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Occasionally it publishes music, film or video game reviews alongside other light content such as comic strips.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The bulletin of the Women's Commission, edited by the Women's Officer of the party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] An irregular email bulletin which summarises the party's recent statements, resolutions, reports and policies.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] It also brings attention to campaigns and events being promoted by the party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] A newspaper for rural communities, produced since March 1936.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] It is run by an editorial collective of Communist and Labour members, environmentalists and trade unionists.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The paper supports the Countryside Charter.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party publishes books under the Manifesto Press imprint.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] it has a total catalogue of 25 titles and also sells 2 titles which are published separately by Hetherington Press.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The books cover historical, political and social topics and are edited by Nick Wright.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] , which operates out of the Unity Books office in Glasgow.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] is a short booklet focused around labour issues and often distributed for free at trade union events.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In addition to this the party publishes many pamphlets under its own name.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The *Classics of Communism* series are reprints of classic works such as *The Communist Manifesto* or *"Left-Wing" Communism: An Infantile Disorder*.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The *Our History* series aims to re-tell 'history from below' and covers historical events from a working class perspective.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] This series is a continuation of the work of the Communist Party Historians Group The party also publishes congress reports, the party programme, briefing notes and other documents.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] At the beginning of November 2004, the party and its youth organisation, the YCL, moved out of its temporary headquarters in Camden, North London after receiving notice to quit because of redevelopment.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The building was owned by AKEL, the Cypriot communist party.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Ruskin House in Croydon was chosen as the new party headquarters, with its long history in the progressive movement as centre of the Anti-Apartheid Movement and also local Labour Party and co-operative groups.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party rents the top floor of four offices at Ruskin House which also allows it plenty of room to hold its congresses and other important meetings, including an annual industrial cadre school and the Communist University of Britain.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In Scotland, the party also makes use of an office in Glasgow.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party holds a biennial congress with delegates from districts, nations and branches.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The last congress as the Communist Party of Great Britain was the 43rd congress and was held in 1991.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The 44th congress, as the Communist Party of Britain, was held in 1997.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] Since 2000 the congress has been held every two years apart from a special congress held in February 2004.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The 29 member governing Executive Committee (EC) of the party is elected at congress.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In November 2004 the party organised Communist University events in Wales and England, these were further developed to form a national three-day event which ran annually from 2005 to 2010.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] This was accompanied by regional weekend universities in Wales, Scotland and the Midlands.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] In 2011, the national Communist University event was renamed to "21st Century Marxism" and the format was changed slightly from a festival to a conference.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The style of the event has changed widely over the years as the organisers experiment with different venues and speakers.
[src:communist-party-of-britain/communist-party-of-britain] The party's political education strategy also includes trade union and political cadre schools, party-building schools and dayschools.
